<HEADLINE> Transplanted Kidneys Now Last Longer  </HEADLINE>
By KATHARINE WEBSTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   Doctors have gotten steadily better at preventing organ
rejection in kidney transplant patients, researchers reported
today, raising hopes of someday easing the nation's shortage of
donor organs.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest problems with organ transplants is that the
patient's immune system may attack the donated organ because it is
not a perfect genetic match. Repeated rejections lead to transplant
failure and the need for another transplant.
</P>
<P>
   There are 44,350 people in the United States waiting for a
kidney transplant. Of those, about 18 percent are waiting for
repeat transplants, according to the United Network for Organ
Sharing, the agency that runs the nation's transplant network.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the last year for which complete figures are available,
12,166 transplants were performed and 2,295 people on the waiting
list died.
</P>
<P>
   A study in today's New England Journal of Medicine looked at all
93,934 kidney transplants done in the United States from 1988
through 1996 and found a steady drop in the rate of rejection.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons include better understanding of how to use
immune-suppressing drugs, earlier detection and treatment of
rejection episodes and better control of infections that take
advantage of the patient's suppressed immune system, said Dr.
Charles Carpenter, an immunologist and kidney expert at Harvard
Medical School who was not involved in the study.
</P>
<P>
   In the study, the proportion of transplanted kidneys from dead
donors that survived the first year after surgery -- the period when
rejection is most likely -- rose from 79 percent to 88 percent. The
survival of transplants from live donors rose from 89 percent to 94
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The expected, median time of survival of the transplanted
kidneys more than doubled from 17 to 36 years among recipients of
organs from living donors (after patients who died of causes other
than transplant failure were excluded). Among recipients of kidneys
from dead donors, it rose from 11 years to 19.5 years.
</P>
<P>
   The prospects for further improvements are good, because the
study did not measure the effects of new anti-rejection drugs that
target specific immune functions instead of shutting down the whole
immune system, Carpenter said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's clear that we can get better even with fine-tuning the
drugs that we have,'' he said. ''And that's what's going to solve
the organ supply, I think, because it's not likely we're going to
be putting pig organs in people any time soon.''
</P>
<P>
   The study was led by Dr. Sundaram Hariharan of the Medical
College of Wisconsin and funded in part by the National Institutes
of Health.
</P>
<P>
   In another study in this week's journal, a new anti-rejection
drug, daclizumab, proved remarkably effective when added to
standard drugs for preventing heart rejection.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers from Columbia-Presbyterian Medical Center compared
27 heart transplant patients who got three standard anti-rejection
drugs with 28 patients who also got daclizumab.
</P>
<P>
   Daclizumab, which shuts down just one type of immune cell, was
administered during the first three months after transplant, the
period when rejection is most likely. The patients were followed
for one year.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that only 18 percent of the patients on
daclizumab suffered an acute rejection episode during the first
three months, compared with 63 percent of those getting standard
drug therapy.
</P>
<P>
   After the daclizumab was discontinued, those patients had nearly
as many first rejection episodes as the control group. But fewer of
them had repeated episodes, and the rejections were much less
severe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
