<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Negotiators Near Aviation Bill Deal  </HEADLINE>
By JIM ABRAMS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Breaking an impasse that has held up federal
airport construction money since last October, congressional
negotiators have agreed on $40 billion in federal aviation
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Budget Committee Chairman Pete Domenici, R-N.M., said
Wednesday that Senate negotiators and House Transportation
Committee Chairman Bud Shuster, R-Pa., ''after numerous meetings
and discussions,'' had agreed on the ''correct approach'' to
handling the Federal Aviation Administration budget.
</P>
<P>
   New spending for airport projects has been on hold since the
fiscal year began last October because a dispute over the status of
the Aviation Trust Fund, which takes in some $10 billion a year
from airport fees and taxes, held up passage of legislation to
authorize FAA spending.
</P>
<P>
   Shuster, a fierce advocate of spending for highways and
aviation, wanted the trust fund to be put ''off-budget,'' meaning
money coming into the fund could be used only for aviation
purposes. Currently revenues from the many federal trust funds go
into the general treasury, and is available for any federal
program.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiators agreed that the trust fund will stay in the
general budget but that funding for aviation programs will at least
equal the amount coming into the trust fund plus interest.
</P>
<P>
   They also decided that the Appropriations Committees that
determine spending every year can assign money from the general
budget to aviation programs, but rejected Shuster's proposal that a
fixed amount of general budget money be set aside to help airports
cope with needs to expand and modernize.
</P>
<P>
   Domenici said funding for federal aviation programs will be $40
billion over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   He said that all the money from the trust fund, some $33 billion
over three years, will be guaranteed for aviation programs, and
that another $6.7 billion will be available to be appropriated from
the general fund.
</P>
<P>
   He said the total amount available for airport projects in 2001
will be $12.7 billion, up $2.7 billion over 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said other issues were still on the table, including the
House proposal that airports be allowed to double the passenger
facility charge, a ticket tax that goes to local improvement
projects, to $6.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
