<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3:15 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thursday, March 2, 2000 
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Pinochet Freed To Return Home
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   LONDON (AP) -- Britain's top law enforcement official ruled today that
former Chilean dictator Gen. Augusto Pinochet should not be extradited to Spain
to stand trial on charges alleging human rights abuses. The long-awaited
decision by Home Secretary Jack Straw freed Pinochet to return home after more
than 16 months of detention. But Spain and the other parties seeking to block
his release could launch last-minute appeals. Straw had announced Jan. 11 that
he was inclined to let the 84-year-old general return to Chile because a medical
examination by four independent doctors had found him medically unfit to stand
trial.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Thousands Still Stranded by Floods
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   MAPUTO, Mozambique (AP) -- With a rescue helicopter hovering overhead and
floodwaters below, Sophia Pedro gave birth to a baby girl in a treetop she had
sought refuge in four days earlier, one of as many as 1 million people made
homeless in this southeast African nation. An hour later, Pedro and her daughter
were rescued after a medic lowered from a helicopter cut the newborn's umbilical
cord and pulled the two to safety. Yesterday's dramatic rescue came as thousands
more Mozambicans remained stranded in trees, on rooftops or on shrinking islands
of land. Thousands more are feared dead in flooding that has devastated one of
the world's poorest countries.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bradley, Gore Fly Overnight to N.Y.
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- After red-eye flights from California, Al Gore and Bill
Bradley are shifting their campaign focus to the East Coast and New York's
crucial primary next week. For Bradley, the stakes are especially high
considering his string of losses, including a drubbing this week in Washington
state where he had invested precious days of campaign time. "If he loses New
York, he's out," former New York City Mayor Edward I. Koch, one of Bradley's
best-known New York supporters, said yesterday. He said the odds for a Bradley
win in New York were not good.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Sliding Euro Pressures Europeans
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- A new low for the beleaguered euro has increased
pressure on the European Central Bank to raise interest rates, but most analysts
predict the bank's governing board will opt to wait when it meets today. The
bank last raised its benchmark rate only a month ago to 3.25 percent from 3.0
percent, saying the weak euro was becoming a flashpoint for inflation. The euro
bounced back to about 99 cents after the Feb. 3 hike, but on Monday it hit a new
low of 93.90 cents before recovering. Yesterday, it hovered at 96.90 cents.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Panel: Implant Brand Safe Enough
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   GAITHERSBURG, Md. (AP) -- A brand of saline-filled breast implants breaks
and leaks much too often -- and many patients must undergo repeated operations
-- but the devices should be allowed to be sold as long women are properly
warned of the risks, a federal advisory panel says. "The choice for a woman is
difficult," bioethicist Nancy Dubler of New York's Montifiore Medical Center
acknowledged yesterday as advisers to the Food and Drug Administration,
following a tense 13 hours of testimony and debate, recommended 8-1 that Mentor
Corp.'s implants stay on the market.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
House Passes Social Security Bill
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- In uncommon election-year bipartisanship, House
Republicans and Democrats united yesterday behind legislation allowing 800,000
senior citizens between ages 65 and 69 to work without fear of losing Social
Security benefits. President Clinton pledged his support. The House voted 422-0
to send the Senate a bill repealing the Social Security earnings limit, a
penalty of $1 in benefits for every $3 a recipient earns over $17,000 this year.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Japan Stocks Close Lower
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   TOKYO (AP) -- On the Tokyo Stock Exchange Thursday, the Nikkei closed down
16.56 points at 20,065.11. In New York Wednesday, the Nasdaq rose 87.39 to close
at 4,784.08, topping the new mark it set Tuesday. The Dow rose 9.62 to
10,137.93.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Lakers Defeat Grizzlies 103-91
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Kobe Bryant had 27 points and Shaquille O'Neal added 25
last night as the Los Angeles Lakers broke open a close game with a flurry of
3-pointers to close the third quarter and beat the Vancouver Grizzlies 103-91
for their 13th consecutive victory. O'Neal, who fouled out with 2:43 left and
the Lakers ahead 95-86, also had 17 rebounds, five assists and five blocks. The
Grizzlies, who have beaten the Lakers only once in the 18 games the teams have
played, kept it close and were up 66-65 when O'Neal drew his fifth foul and went
to the bench late in the third quarter.
</P>
