<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 07:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Corporate Sponsors Take to Broadway  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL KUCHWARA, AP Drama Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- If you haven't yet seen the involvement of
corporate America on Broadway, soon you won't be able to miss it.
</P>
<P>
   The nonprofit Roundabout Theater Company will rechristen its
newly renovated 42nd Street home the American Airlines Theater
because of an $8.5 million company gift, spread over a 10-year
period.
</P>
<P>
   It's the latest in a series of corporate forays onto Broadway
that have led to closer ties to the world of big business and
high-powered marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Shubert Organization, Broadway's largest theater owner,
is rumored to be considering a deal with General Motors to rename
the Winter Garden, home of ''Cats,'' as the Cadillac Winter Garden.
</P>
<P>
   The Roundabout, which has 45,000 subscribers, has an annual
budget of more than $20 million. Its successes include the current
revival of ''Cabaret'' and the critically praised production of
''Anna Christie'' starring Natasha Richardson and Liam Neeson.
</P>
<P>
   ''This generous investment will provide Roundabout with the
critical financial stability to continue the caliber of work and
programs our audiences have come to expect,'' said Todd Haimes, the
company's artistic director.
</P>
<P>
   In return for its gift, the airline will get its name on the
theater's marquee, as well as on tickets and advertising, for the
length of the partnership.
</P>
<P>
   The theater opened in 1918 and was built and named for producer
Arch Selwyn. It became a movie house in the 1930s and languished
for years until the rebirth of activity in the Times Square area in
the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The space, which has undergone a $21 million, two-year
renovation, opens in April with a revival of ''Uncle Vanya,''
starring Derek Jacobi.
</P>
<P>
   The renaming of Broadway theaters is not new, although in the
past it usually has been done with a theatrical connection in mind.
Names of theaters have been changed to honor playwrights (Eugene
O'Neill), actors (Alfred Lunt and Lynn Fontanne), composers
(Richard Rodgers) and even critics (Brooks Atkinson and Walter
Kerr).
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, now-defunct Livent combined two theaters on 42nd
Street, the Apollo and Lyric, and called its new playhouse the Ford
Center for the Performing Arts.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is a growing trend,'' said producer Alexander Cohen. ''It
will accelerate the marketing, merchandising and even the
politicization of Broadway as we know it.
</P>
<P>
   ''One cannot be too critical of anything supportive of the
theater,'' said Cohen, who was instrumental in getting Broadway
theaters renamed for Rodgers and George and Ira Gershwin. ''At the
same time one has to pay respect to those who created the American
theater. We do not need the Campbell's Pork and Beans Palace.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-02-00 0722 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
