<HEADLINE> Discriminatory Rates Investigated  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Department of Housing and Urban
Development is investigating whether the two biggest underwriters
of home mortgages discriminate against blacks and other minorities,
The Washington Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of black Americans pay higher mortgage rates or may
not be able to get a mortgage at all because of lending policies at
Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The absence of active involvement by Fannie Mae and Freddie
Mac in these markets limits the opportunities for African-American
families to get conventional mortgages,'' the Post quoted William
Apgar, HUD's federal housing commissioner, as saying.
</P>
<P>
   HUD is preparing to release a 500-page proposal, possibly as
early as today, with rules to require the companies to do more
business with underserved consumers, the Post said. In the
proposal, the agency says the percentage of loans to blacks that
Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac buy lags behind the percentage of home
loans made to blacks nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac spokesmen said the numbers HUD uses
overstate the difference and don't reflect their efforts to expand
the loan market for blacks, the Post said.
</P>
<P>
   Freddie Mac and Fannie Mae gives lenders the ability to make
more loans by buying home loans from banks and other mortgage
lenders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-02-00 0722 </TRAILER>
