<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Up 16.05; Nasdaq Down 2.73  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed at the start of trading today
as investors grew more cautious as they awaited the government's
employment report on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was up 16.05 at 10,153.98.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were slightly lower. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index was down 1.51 at 1,377.68, and the Nasdaq
composite index was down 2.73 at 4,781.35.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart led the Dow higher, rising 2 13/16 to 52 and helping
the blue-chip index extend a three-day streak of gains. In the
first three sessions of this week, the Dow regained 275 of the 357
points it lost last week.
</P>
<P>
   But the interest rate worries responsible for the Dow's plunge
last week clearly are still in the market, traders said. This
morning, most leading retail companies reported robust sales,
suggesting Americans are spending freely despite four rate
increases by the Federal Reserve since last June.
</P>
<P>
   Higher rates make it more expensive to borrow money. The Fed has
been raising rates in an effort to slow the economy to a pace that
will allow continued growth without inflation.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, investors will receive a crucial piece of information
on the economy's strength when the government releases its
employment report for the month of February. The report will
include information on wages and benefits, which should indicate
whether companies are spending heavily to attract and keep
employees while the U.S. jobless rate lingers at extremely low
levels.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks, which have held up best amid growing worries
over interest rates, slipped back today as investors took some
profits from their recent run. Sun Microsystems was down 1~ at 96
1/16 and Intel fell 1 7/16 to 114 7/16.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 6-to-5 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 177.47 million
shares, behind Wednesday's brisk pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 1.05 to 587.30.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.1 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was down 1.0 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was down 0.5 percent, and France's CAC-40 was
up 1.0 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
