<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sen.: State Department Is Top-Heavy  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY SCHWEID, AP Diplomatic Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The chairman of the Senate Appropriations
Committee complained today that the State Department is top-heavy
with senior policy-makers far in excess of normal needs.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department, which is larger, operates with fewer
senior officials, Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, told Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright at a subcommittee hearing on the Clinton
administration's request for $23.7 billion for foreign policy
operations in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ''That has a lot to do with the funding problems of your
department,'' Stevens said.
</P>
<P>
   While Albright and other administration officials say the money
spent on foreign operations is only a tiny fraction of overall
spending, various parts of the budget have come under attack on
Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, for instance, Rep. Harold Rogers, R-Ky., chairman
of the House Appropriations subcommittee that oversees the State
Department budget, said the $739 million requested for peacekeeping
operations would fund missions ''which seem to offer little hope
for success.''
</P>
<P>
   The administration is seeking a 220 percent increase, he said.
Rogers told Albright ''You all seem to have Mae West's view of
things: 'Too much of a good thing is simply wonderful,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens lodged his complaint softly. He said the proliferation
of assistant secretaries of state and other senior posts ''is
something we should look at and not get into a political wrangle
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright assured him there was an ongoing review at the
department. She also defended the bureaucracy, noting there are 187
countries in the United Nations. ''This is a large world and we
need officers capable of dealing with these countries,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Albright said, ''We often don't have enough foreign
service officers to do the job.''
</P>
<P>
   She said significant increases were being requested only for
security and U.N. peacekeeping programs.
</P>
<P>
   But Stevens insisted that the way the department is structured,
''the money is going to the topside too much.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Albright notified the subcommittee that she may
create an undersecretary of state post to deal with security and
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   The idea, she said, was to have ''a single high-ranking officer
who can speak for the department on security questions.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a step forward,'' Rogers assured her. ''It's welcome
news.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, President Clinton signed a directive for a new $10
million program to train foreign police forces under a new office
at the department.
</P>
</TEXT>
