<HEADLINE> Dow Up 51.19; Nasdaq Up 29.67  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mostly higher today as investors
continued to buy blue chip stocks that were battered last week as
well as the technology stocks that have led the market this year.
</P>
<P>
   In morning trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 51.19 at 10,189.12.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index was up 4.26 at 1,383.45, and the Nasdaq composite index
was up 39.67 at 4,823.75.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T led the Dow higher, rising 4 3/16 to 52. In the first three
sessions of this week, the Dow regained 275 of the 357 points it
lost last week.
</P>
<P>
   Investors believe ''enough was enough'' after last week's
pummeling of Dow and other industrial stocks, said Gregory Nie,
technical analyst at First Union Securities in Chicago. ''This
week, volume has picked up and breadth is better, and the market is
trying to rally. That is encouraging.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft rose 3 3/16 to 94 and Exxon Mobil, boosted by the
latest spike in oil prices, rose 2 5/16 to 77 1/16.
</P>
<P>
   But the interest rate worries responsible for the Dow's plunge
last week clearly are still in the market and contributing to
volatility, traders said. This morning, most leading retail
companies reported robust sales, suggesting Americans are spending
freely despite four rate increases by the Federal Reserve since
last June.
</P>
<P>
   Higher rates make it more expensive to borrow money. The Fed has
been raising rates in an effort to slow the economy to a pace that
will allow continued growth without inflation.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, investors will receive a crucial piece of information
on the economy's strength when the government releases its
employment report for the month of February. The report will
include information on wages and benefits, which should indicate
whether companies are spending heavily to attract and keep
employees while the U.S. jobless rate lingers at extremely low
levels.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks, which have held up best amid growing worries
over interest rates, were also higher today. Radiant Systems soared
39} to 95 after the company said it will work with Microsoft to
develop electronic commerce systems.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Palm Inc., the spinoff of 3Com Corp., had not yet
begun trading on the Nasdaq. Palm shares were priced at 38 late
Wednesday, well above original estimates of 14 to 16 per share.
Parent company 3Com rose 5] to 109{ today.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 6-to-5 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 404.59 million
shares, ahead of Wednesday's brisk pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 0.46 to 588.81.
</P>
</TEXT>
