<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 11:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rough start for all-female policy  </HEADLINE>
By JIM FITZGERALD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   VALHALLA, N.Y. (AP) -- Two correction officers at the Westchester
County Jail who were reassigned under a new policy barring male
guards from the women's quarters did not show up for their first
shifts overnight and county officials worried briefly about the
possibility of a job action.
</P>
<P>
   But the day shift went more smoothly and spokesman Terry Kelly
said the county was no longer concerned. A union lawyer said the
two absent officers had ''completely legitimate medical reasons.''
He would not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   The two guards -- a man who had been transferred out of the
women's unit and a woman who had been transferred in -- claimed
unspecified on-the-job injuries and did not come in for the 11 p.m.
shift Wednesday, the first under the new policy, said county
spokeswoman Susan Tolchin. One reassigned male guard did work, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'll be watching closely to see if this is the sign of
something bigger,'' she said late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   At 7 a.m. Thursday, six reassigned officers were scheduled in,
and all but one -- a woman who called in sick -- reported, Kelly
said.
</P>
<P>
   In all, 14 male officers and 14 females were reassigned on the
orders of County Executive Andrew Spano after the Jan. 26 arrests
of four male officers for alleged sexual attacks on female inmates.
</P>
<P>
   ''We cannot allow a climate where this type of behavior can go
on,'' Spano said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Goodstein, attorney for the 754-member Correction
Officers Benevolent Association, had said the new policy would be
obeyed, but called it illegal and vowed a court challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's sexual discrimination against the men,'' he said. ''This
is guilt by association because they happen to be the same sex (as
the accused men). It is ludicrous.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocco Pozzi, the county's correction commissioner, insisted that
the change is permitted under the work contract.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, housing posts in the women's jail were assigned on a
seniority basis, and most went to men, since they were the officers
with the most time in.
</P>
<P>
   The jail houses women who are either awaiting trial or serving
sentences of up to one year. It currently holds about 150 inmates.
</P>
<P>
   The county and the prison guards union have had contentious
relations for years, with the county claiming that correction
officers abuse their disability and overtime privileges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
