<HEADLINE> Dow Up 37.23; Nasdaq Up 22.53  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mostly higher today as investors
continued to buy blue chip stocks that were battered last week and
made room for a highly-anticipated new offering in the technology
sector.
</P>
<P>
   In midday trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 37.23 at 10,175.16.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were modestly higher. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index was up 2.51 at 1,381.70, and the Nasdaq composite
index was up 22.53 at 4,806.61.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T led the Dow higher, rising 5 1/16 to 52~. In the first
three sessions of this week, the Dow regained 275 of the 357 points
it lost last week.
</P>
<P>
   Investors believe ''enough was enough'' after last week's
pummeling of Dow and other industrial stocks, said Gregory Nie,
technical analyst at First Union Securities in Chicago. ''This
week, volume has picked up and breadth is better, and the market is
trying to rally. That is encouraging.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft rose 3 3/16 to 94 and Exxon Mobil, boosted by the
latest spike in oil prices, rose 1{ to 76\.
</P>
<P>
   On the Nasdaq, Palm Inc., the spinoff of 3Com Corp., soared to
102{ from its offering price of 38 per share. Parent company 3Com,
which has risen sharply in recent sessions, tumbled 14 1/16 to 90
1/16 today.
</P>
<P>
   Companies poised to take advantage of the growth of the Internet
were also higher today. Radiant Systems soared 35 13/16 to 91 1/16
after the company said it will work with Microsoft to develop
electronic commerce systems.
</P>
<P>
   While most stocks were higher, trading was fairly volatile,
indicating that the interest rate worries responsible for the Dow's
plunge last week clearly are still in the market.
</P>
<P>
   This morning, most leading retail companies reported robust
sales, suggesting Americans are spending freely despite four rate
increases by the Federal Reserve since last June.
</P>
<P>
   Higher rates make it more expensive to borrow money. The Fed has
been raising rates in an effort to slow the economy to a pace that
will allow continued growth without inflation.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, investors will receive a crucial piece of information
on the economy's strength when the government releases its
employment report for the month of February. The report will
include information on wages and benefits, which should indicate
whether companies are spending heavily to attract and keep
employees while the U.S. jobless rate lingers at extremely low
levels.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 4-to-3 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 569.20 million
shares, ahead of Wednesday's brisk pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies slipped 0.43 to
587.92.
</P>
</TEXT>
