<HEADLINE> Dixie Chicks, Hill, McGraw Nominated  </HEADLINE>
By JIM PATTERSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- The Dixie Chicks, Faith Hill and her
husband, Tim McGraw, lead the field in nominations for Academy of
Country Music Awards, with newcomer Brad Paisley close at their
heels.
</P>
<P>
   Nominations were announced Wednesday evening at the Country
Radio Seminar, an annual country music convention. Winners will be
announced May 3 during a ceremony at Universal City, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   McGraw, Hill and the Dixie Chicks were each nominated in five
categories including the top award of best entertainer. Hill and
McGraw were also nominated for albums or singles they both sang on
and produced.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to best entertainer, McGraw is up for best male
vocalist, album (''A Place in the Sun''), single and song (''Please
Remember Me''). Hill got nods for best female vocalist, song
(''Breathe''), and album (''Breathe'').
</P>
<P>
   Paisley's song, ''He Didn't Have to Be,'' proved a favorite of
the 3,000 music industry workers who nominate and choose the award
winners. The song, about the relationship between a boy and his
stepfather, was nominated for best single, song and video. Paisley
was also nominated for best new male vocalist, with Gary Allan and
Chad Brock.
</P>
<P>
   Country music great George Jones, who had a near-fatal
automobile accident in March 1999, capped a comeback year with
three nominations: best album for ''Cold Hard Truth,'' best song
for ''Choices,'' and best vocal event or a collaboration with Chad
Brock and Hank Williams Jr. on Williams' ''A Country Boy Can
Survive.'' Just last week, ''Choices'' won Jones the Grammy for
best male country vocal.
</P>
<P>
   Garth Brooks didn't get any nominations after winning best
entertainer and top artist of the decade at the 1999 awards
ceremony. He spent much of 1999 promoting a pop music album
recorded under the alias Chris Gaines.
</P>
<P>
   The full list of nominees:
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINER: Dixie Chicks, Faith Hill, Tim McGraw, Sawyer Brown,
Shania Twain.
</P>
<P>
   MALE VOCALIST: Alan Jackson, Toby Keith, Tim McGraw, Collin
Raye, George Strait.
</P>
<P>
   FEMALE VOCALIST: Faith Hill, Martina McBride, Jo Dee Messina,
Shania Twain, Chely Wright.
</P>
<P>
   DUET OR GROUP: Asleep at the Wheel, Brooks &AMP; Dunn, Dixie Chicks,
Lonestar, Sawyer Brown.
</P>
<P>
   NEW MALE VOCALIST: Gary Allan, Chad Brock, Brad Paisley.
</P>
<P>
   NEW FEMALE VOCALIST: Jessica Andrews, Julie Reeves, Chalee
Tennison.
</P>
<P>
   NEW GROUP OR DUET: Montgomery Gentry, SHeDAISY, Yankee Grey.
</P>
<P>
   ALBUM: ''A Place in the Sun,'' Tim McGraw; ''Breathe,'' Faith
Hill; ''Cold Hard Truth,'' George Jones; ''Fly,'' Dixie Chicks;
''Ride With Bob,'' Asleep at the Wheel.
</P>
<P>
   SONG: ''Amazed,'' Lonestar; ''Breathe,'' Faith Hill;
''Choices,'' George Jones; ''He Didn't Have to Be,'' Brad Paisley;
''Please Remember Me,'' Tim McGraw.
</P>
<P>
   SINGLE RECORD: ''Amazed,'' Lonestar; ''He Didn't Have to Be,''
Brad Paisley; ''Please Remember Me,'' Tim McGraw; ''Ready to Run,'
Dixie Chicks; ''Write This Down,'' George Strait.
</P>
<P>
   VOCAL EVENT OF THE YEAR: ''A Country Boy can Survive,'' Chad
Brock with Hank Williams Jr. and George Jones; ''After the Gold
Rush,'' Emmylou Harris, Dolly Parton and Linda Ronstadt; ''God Must
Have Spent a Little More Time on You,'' Alabama and 'N Sync; ''My
Kind of Woman,'' Vince Gill and Patty Loveless; ''When I Said I
Do,'' Clint Black with Lisa Hartman Black.
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO: ''Breathe,'' Faith Hill; ''He Didn't Have to Be,'' Brad
Paisley; ''How Do You Like Me Now,'' Toby Keith; ''Ready to Run,''
Dixie Chicks; ''Single White Female,'' Chely Wright.
</P>
</TEXT>
