<HEADLINE> Clinton: HMO Bill Must OK Lawsuits  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton said today he will veto a
bill governing how Americans deal with their health plans if it
does not allow patients to sue HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   ''I will not sign legislation ... that is a patient's bill of
rights in name only,'' Clinton said at a White House rally timed to
coincide with the attempt in Congress this week to compromise the
touchy issue.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not a real patient's bill of rights if it denies people
the right to see a specialist, if it fails to guarantee access to
the nearest emergency room care, if it denies the right to stay
with the health care provider throughout a course of treatment,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   He would also veto a bill ''if it doesn't include a strong
enforcement mechanism to hold the health care plan accountable,''
Clinton said. Clinton has long supported a patient's right to sue,
and the ''enforcement mechanism'' translates to the ability to take
health plans to court if the plan denies needed care.
</P>
<P>
   The House and Senate passed bills that offer patient
protections, but they differ on liability and who would be covered.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill, supported by the White House, Democrats and many
Republicans, allows lawsuits and covers 161 million Americans with
private insurance. The Senate bill, crafted by Republicans, doesn't
allow lawsuits and covers 55 million Americans whose health plans
are exempt from state regulations.
</P>
<P>
   A bipartisan group of House members and senators came to the
White House today to endorse the House approach. A House-Senate
conference hopes to write a compromise bill by March 31.
</P>
<P>
   Insurers and corporations vehemently oppose a right to sue,
arguing it will raise premiums. They've conducted their own polls
suggesting many workers would lose coverage because companies,
fearing lawsuits, would stop offering health plans.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton acknowledged that he was ''preaching to the saved'' at
today's rally.
</P>
<P>
   ''I ask you to remember that the work is ahead of us. We need to
all of us, each in our own way, go to work to impress upon that
conference committee their profound responsibility,'' Clinton said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
