<HEADLINE> Justice Encourages Children To Read  </HEADLINE>
By LAURIE ASSEO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sporting a ''Cat in the Hat'' necktie, Supreme
Court Justice Stephen G. Breyer joined a national reading promotion
Thursday by leading a group of schoolchildren in a special pledge
to read every day.
</P>
<P>
   ''I promise to read each day and each night, I know it's the key
to growing up right,'' he said as 18 third- and fourth-graders from
Watkins Elementary School in Washington repeated the rhyming, Dr.
Seuss-style pledge after him.
</P>
<P>
   ''OK, you're all first-class readers,'' Breyer told the kids.
''That's great.''
</P>
<P>
   The session in the court building's ornate library was part of
the National Education Association's ''Read Across America''
promotion on the birthday of the late Theodor Geisel, author of the
Dr. Seuss books.
</P>
<P>
   With the children sitting on the floor and wearing large
red-and-white Dr. Seuss hats, Breyer read aloud the book
''Marshall, the Courthouse Mouse,'' a story of a court made up of
nine mice ''justices'' deciding a lawsuit over what kind of cheese
the citizens can eat.
</P>
<P>
   The children seemed to like the story, but most of all they
enjoyed hearing about the private gym on the floor above the
Supreme Court's library.
</P>
<P>
   ''Can you keep a secret?'' Breyer said. ''You know what's above
this? A basketball court.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Oooh!'' the children responded.
</P>
<P>
   And Breyer told the children how he became one of the nine
justices on the nation's highest court.
</P>
<P>
   ''I started out at school just like you,'' he said.
''Eventually, I went to law school and then I became a law
teacher.''
</P>
<P>
   ''You have to be quite lucky to be a judge. It depends on other
people who think you would be a good judge,'' Breyer said.
''Eventually, I was appointed to this court. ... That's what
happens throughout life. You try to do as well as you can.''
</P>
</TEXT>
