<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley's wife is a German scholar, freewheeling campaigner  </HEADLINE>
By LAURENCE ARNOLD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- When Bill Bradley visited his Princeton
University pal Dan Okimoto in Tokyo in 1970, he brought along a
surprise.
</P>
<P>
   With him was Ernestine Schlant, a German-born professor. She was
eight years Bradley's senior. She showed little interest in his
high-profile career in professional basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Things made sense to Okimoto when he and his wife, and Bradley
and Schlant, took a hike along a lake, discussing the comparative
attributes of German and Japanese literature.
</P>
<P>
   ''She would walk two steps ahead, craning her neck to look back
at who was talking,'' Okimoto said. ''I thought wow, this woman is
a powerhouse.''
</P>
<P>
   In Ernestine, whom he married in 1974, Bradley found a partner
for his passions. In basketball, then in Congress, Bradley looked
for any chance to study and to see the world. In Ernestine, he
chose a wife who grew up in Germany during World War II and, ever
since, has immersed herself in learning.
</P>
<P>
   On the campus of Montclair State University in New Jersey she is
Professor Schlant, author of three books including, most recently,
''The Language of Silence: West German Literature and the
Holocaust.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to English and German, she speaks French, passable
Spanish, and Italian ''if I can speak with my hands.'' That's on
top of six years of Latin in school and two years of Russian.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike her husband, who can come across as somber, Ernestine
Bradley sometimes seems downright bubbly. She is 64 but barely
suppresses a girlish giggle as an admirer gives her a glowing
introduction. Her knees act like shock absorbers as she throws
herself into a speech.
</P>
<P>
   She is susceptible to the occasional English-as-second-language
malapropism. At one campaign appearance she urged listeners not to
trust ''pollings'' and criticized the Clinton administration's
''don't talk, don't tell'' policy on gays in the military.
</P>
<P>
   Violating a commandment for political spouses, she also confides
in her audience that she disagreed with her husband's decision to
hold a question-and-answer session on foreign policy rather than
deliver a formal address.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am not a politician,'' she says later, explaining her
candor, ''so I can be floating around in the idealistic sphere.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley likes to joke, ''My wife says I like strong women,
which means I really love HER.''
</P>
<P>
   Born Ernestine Misslbeck, she grew up in the Bavarian city of
Passau. During the war, a Nazi slave-labor camp operated just two
miles away -- a fact she says she learned years later.
</P>
<P>
   Her late father, Sepp, worked in ground support with the German
air force -- the Luftwaffe -- but was not, she emphasizes, a member
of the Nazi Party. She says he never revealed his thoughts about
the Nazi campaign against the Jews.
</P>
<P>
   There was some concern her roots would be used against her
husband in national politics.
</P>
<P>
   ''We talked long ago that this might be an issue,'' said
Ernestine Bradley, an American citizen for 37 years. ''Bill does
not think this would be an issue. And frankly I hoped this would
not be an issue, because if it did become an issue, it would show
that people are not voting for Bill, but for my past. I don't think
people would do that.''
</P>
<P>
   A job as ''air hostess'' for Pan Am brought Ernestine to the
United States in 1957. At Emory University in Atlanta she earned an
undergraduate degree in Romance languages, then a master's and
doctorate in comparative literature. She also married Robert
Schlant, had a child and divorced. Her daughter from that marriage,
Stephanie, has four children.
</P>
<P>
   An unplanned second course of study at Emory was her personal
history. In discussions with her adviser, a Jewish immigrant, she
learned more about the Holocaust and how close it had come to her
childhood home in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   On subsequent trips back to Germany to visit family -- her ailing
mother, Erna, and a brother, Sepp, still live there -- she asked
questions about the war.
</P>
<P>
   ''Basically,'' she recalled, ''there was a silence.''
</P>
<P>
   So, she embarked on what has become a 35-year academic career
dedicated to learning about the Holocaust. Ten years of work
culminated in the release last February of ''The Language of
Silence.'' In it, she contends that postwar German novelists
skirted the painful issues and memories left over.
</P>
<P>
   The same could not be said of her. Shortly after the U.S.
Holocaust Museum opened in 1993, she toured it along with Rita
Jacobs, a Jewish friend who lost numerous relatives in the
Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   Together, they cried.
</P>
<P>
   ''She was the best person I could go with,'' said Jacobs, who
also is a professor at Montclair State. ''She understood what it
meant.''
</P>
<P>
   On a break from teaching in 1970, Ernestine was working for a
New York documentary production company and living in the same
Manhattan building as Bradley, a star forward for the New York
Knicks. The company asked Schlant to slip a note under his door
proposing that he interview poet Marianne Moore, a sports fan, for
a documentary.
</P>
<P>
   The project was scrubbed when Moore fell ill, but Bradley and
Schlant began dating. They married in 1974. Their daughter, Theresa
Ann, is 23.
</P>
<P>
   Diagnosed with breast cancer in 1992, Mrs. Bradley underwent a
mastectomy and chemotherapy and emerged with the belief that in
cancer, too, language has the power to stigmatize. She now tries to
avoid words like ''victim'' or ''survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   And she remains careful with her words when asked to look ahead
to what she would do as first lady.
</P>
<P>
   ''I consider my situation right now like walking on a
tightrope,'' she said. ''I'm going every day, one step, and I think
if I looked further down that line I'd get dizzy and for sure would
fall.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
