<DOCNO> APW20000302.0034 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley and Gore fly overnight to New York  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Al Gore read to a class of 5-year-olds and
Bill Bradley headed for a hot dog restaurant today as the
Democratic presidential hopefuls shifted their campaigns east to
focus on New York's crucial primary next week.
</P>
<P>
   For Bradley, the stakes were especially high after a string of
losses left even some of his supporters predicting his campaign
wouldn't last long past Super Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Bradley seemed jovial. After a red-eye flight from
California, where the candidates met Wednesday night in a low-key
debate, he joked with reporters about the grueling pace.
</P>
<P>
   ''I slept for two hours -- that's all you need for a hot dog
stand,'' Bradley said before his planned visit to meet, greet and
eat at the popular hot dog spot, Gray's Papaya.
</P>
<P>
   Afterwards he was flying to Connecticut -- like New York, a state
where the Bradley campaign believes it has a chance to win Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Gore picked up an informal endorsement from former Vice
President Walter F. Mondale today, and stopped at the Alfred E.
Smith public school to read to children gathered around his feet.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the conviction of one of his supporters for
arranging illegal contributions in 1996 to the Clinton-Gore
campaign and other Democrats, Gore called Maria Hsia ''a friend and
political supporter.''
</P>
<P>
   ''A jury has rendered its verdict. It's a hard day for her,'' he
said, declining further comment.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's state headquarters tried to remain upbeat -- staffers
answered the phone, ''It can happen in New York'' -- Gore's camp
sought victory and launched radio ads Wednesday specifically
tailored to the state's black and Hispanic communities.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of the importance placed on New York, Gore and
Bradley, and Republican contenders George W. Bush and John McCain,
planned to dart in and out of the state over the next five days.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's schedule has him campaigning in New York on Friday and
Saturday with Gov. George Pataki and New York City Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani, who is running for the U.S. Senate against Hillary Rodham
Clinton. McCain was campaigning here tonight and Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the state's importance to his campaign, Bradley, who
became famous playing basketball with the New York Knicks, had been
strangely absent since Feb. 23. Instead, he concentrated on
Washington state where he had hoped a strong showing would
rejuvenate his sagging campaign.
</P>
<P>
   He lost badly.
</P>
<P>
   While Bradley has backing from Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan and
former Mayor Edward I. Koch, most of the state's top elected
Democrats and its powerful labor unions are supporting Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Three statewide polls Wednesday showed Gore with huge leads over
Bradley. The Marist College Institute for Public Opinion had the
vice president ahead, 61 percent to 29 percent, among likely
Democratic primary voters in New York. At the end of last year,
Bradley was running even with Gore or leading in New York where 243
delegates are at stake next Tuesday
</P>
<P>
   In Minneapolis, Mondale told WCCO Radio today he promised Gore
his support recently ''and I guess I'm announcing it now.'' The
1984 Democratic nominee plans to appear with Gore in Minnesota next
week.
</P>
<P>
   On the Republican side, where 93 delegates are up for grabs,
statewide polls have shown McCain slightly ahead of Bush or running
even with the Texas governor.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is counting on his statehouse colleague, Pataki, to
deliver.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki warned Wednesday that Bush was in for a ''difficult
fight,'' and the governor appeared intent on avoiding blame for a
possible loss. ''Ultimately, it comes down to the candidates,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Pataki and state GOP Chairman William Powers delivered
all of New York's GOP delegates to Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, McCain is hoping to make inroads, especially
among the 46 percent of New York's Republican voters who are Roman
Catholic and may be sympathetic to complaints about Bush's visit to
a South Carolina university whose leaders have expressed
anti-Catholic views.
</P>
<P>
   Aware of the potential problem with Catholic voters, Bush wrote
an apologetic letter to Cardinal John O'Connor of New York. Bush
also plans to march in a St. Patrick's Day parade Sunday in
Binghamton and visit Canisius College, a Catholic school, in
Buffalo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
