<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swimming hero had to choose between friend, struggling girl  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY BAIR, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- In the chaos of a rescue off New Jersey's
beaches, Dominic McClinton had to pick whose life he would save.
</P>
<P>
   He could rescue his friend since boyhood, a 29-year-old
construction worker who had rushed into the Atlantic Ocean after a
struggling girl despite being unable to swim. Or he could save a
9-year-old girl whom he had never met.
</P>
<P>
   McClinton, who was honored Thursday with 18 others for heroism
by the Carnegie Hero Fund Commission of Pittsburgh, said his first
instinct was to push Kelly Thomas toward a wall of rocks that
jutted into the water off Atlantic City, N.J., on July 25, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, McClinton could see that Andre Corbitt was struggling
with the current. He said he could have reached out and touched
Corbitt and was trying to find a way to save both him and the girl.
</P>
<P>
   ''I told her, 'I am going to push you. Swim to the rocks. You
can make it.' She kept saying, 'Mister, please don't let me go.'
She grabbed onto me,'' said McClinton, also 29, of Germantown, Md.,
and an employee of a Hilton in suburban Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The former lifeguard swam about 50 yards to the rocks with the
girl in his arms and was unable to spot Corbitt when he turned
around.
</P>
<P>
   He ran to the end of the rocks in his bare feet, bloodying them,
to try to find Corbitt but believes he was swept away by the strong
evening tide. A second boy who was swimming with Kelly had been
rescued earlier.
</P>
<P>
   McClinton spent summers in Atlantic City with relatives and
friends including Corbitt, of Pleasantville, whose sister he once
dated and whom he often saw at barbecues.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a natural reaction to try to help. What people don't
understand is how close the kids were to the shore. The water just
suddenly drops off out there,'' McClinton said. ''(Corbitt)
probably just thought he could walk out there until the water was
up to his neck.''
</P>
<P>
   Corbitt's body was found three days later. He was also honored
Thursday by the Pittsburgh-based commission, which was started in
1904 by industrialist Andrew Carnegie. The heroes or their
relatives each get $3,500 and a bronze medal.
</P>
<P>
   Honorees included Todd Williams, 32, an oil driller from Port
Burwell, Ontario, Canada. Williams climbed into the cab of a
runaway tractor-trailer and stopped it at the crest of a hill on a
highway near Guelph on Oct. 7, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The rig had been swerving across the road and nearly hit the car
that Williams' sister was driving.
</P>
<P>
   Williams then perched himself on the window of his sister's car
and saw there was no one at the wheel of the truck. The driver,
Edward McCleod, was lying on the floor of the cab, having a fatal
heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   Williams next persuaded his sister, who called him ''nuts,'' to
speed ahead. He jumped out and ran, grabbed onto a rail on the
truck's body and was briefly dragged alongside at 30 mph before
pulling himself up to the cab.
</P>
<P>
   ''It peeled the bottoms off my boots,'' Williams said Thursday
from Alberta, where he was placing explosives for a new well.
</P>
<P>
   ''I lead a thrilling life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was familiar with trucks from a former job in a plywood
yard, so it was no trouble for him to stop McCleod's
tractor-trailer with the brakes. But he was unable to revive the
trucker despite several minutes of cardiopulmonary resuscitation.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I sat him up, he gasped for air three times. I said,
'Come on, do it again,' but he didn't. Then I threw him into the
sleeper part of his cab. I did CPR on him to the point of
exhaustion,'' Williams said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
