<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Down 48.47; DowUp 0.31  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks turned mostly lower today as investors
took profits from a recent rise in technology stocks, making room
for new issues like the highly anticipated offering from Palm Inc.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-afternoon trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was up 0.31 at 10,138.24.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mostly lower. The Nasdaq composite
index was down 48.47 at 4,735.61 after giving up a gain of as much
as 44 points. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 4.81 at
1,374.78.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq slumped despite an explosive initial public offering
from Palm Inc., the spinoff of 3Com Corp. Shares of Palm soared to
103 from its offering price of 38 per share. Parent company 3Com,
which has risen sharply in recent sessions, tumbled 16~ to 87\
today.
</P>
<P>
   Several other prominent technology companies slipped, suggesting
that investors were selling shares of companies that have performed
well this year to raise cash to buy lesser-known names in the
technology and Internet fields.
</P>
<P>
   Radiant Systems, for example, soared 38 5/16 to 93 9/16 after
the company said it will work with Microsoft to develop electronic
commerce systems.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow industrials held up better than the technology-heavy
Nasdaq as investors continued to seek out stocks that fell last
week, when the Dow tumbled 357 points.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T led the Dow higher, rising 5 1/16 to 52~.
</P>
<P>
   Investors believe ''enough was enough'' after last week's
pummeling of Dow and other industrial stocks, said Gregory Nie,
technical analyst at First Union Securities in Chicago. ''This
week, volume has picked up and breadth is better, and the market is
trying to rally. That is encouraging.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft rose 2 to 92 13/16 and Exxon Mobil, boosted by the
latest spike in oil prices, rose 1 9/16 to 76 5/16.
</P>
<P>
   Trading was fairly volatile, indicating that the interest rate
worries responsible for the Dow's plunge last week clearly are
still in the market.
</P>
<P>
   This morning, most leading retail companies reported robust
sales, suggesting Americans are spending freely despite four rate
increases by the Federal Reserve since last June.
</P>
<P>
   Higher rates make it more expensive to borrow money. The Fed has
been raising rates in an effort to slow the economy to a pace that
will allow continued growth without inflation.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, investors will receive a crucial piece of information
on the economy's strength when the government releases its
employment report for the month of February. The report will
include information on wages and benefits, which should indicate
whether companies are spending heavily to attract and keep
employees while the U.S. jobless rate lingers at extremely low
levels.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 4-to-3 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 817.99 million
shares, slightly behind Wednesday's brisk pace.
</P>
<P>
   Profit-taking also hurt the Russell 2000 index of smaller
companies, which fell 6.11 to 582.24. That index hit a new record
on Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
