<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 15:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Helps Air Base Developer  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT BURNS, AP Military Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Pentagon will forgive $103 million of debt
owed to the Air Force by the Greater Kelly Development Authority, a
San Antonio-based group that is redeveloping the soon-to-close
Kelly Air Force Base, Texas, officials said today.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen's spokesman, Kenneth Bacon, said
Cohen announced the decision today in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   The authority had agreed to pay the Air Force $108 million for
the land and redevelop it as a business park. Using authority
granted by the Congress last year, Cohen erased all but $5 million
of that debt, Bacon said. It is the first time the Pentagon has
used the debt-forgiveness authority.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen's decision is intended to make it easier for local
communities with an economic stake in a military base targeted for
closure to convert it to private commercial use. Many such
communities have complained that the process is too expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly was among a large number of military bases designated for
closure by the federal government in 1995. The 4,700-acre base is a
military depot and was a major employer in the San Antonio area. It
is due to close by 2001. About half of Kelly's land is being
conveyed to the authority, and the other half is being made part of
nearby Lackland Air Force Base.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Cohen told Congress that the Pentagon needs
authority to conduct two more rounds of base closures. At the same
time, however, the service chiefs were sounding a less enthusiastic
note.
</P>
<P>
   ''As the smallest service with the fewest number of bases, I
know of no installation that I would recommend be closed in the
Marine Corps,'' Gen. James Jones, the Marine Corps commandant, told
the Senate Armed Services Committee on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Adm. Jay Johnson, the chief of naval operations, said his view
was ''not far'' from Jones's.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said a round of base closings ''probably needs to
happen.'' He is concerned that in opening up a national debate on
how and where to reduce the military's land holdings, the Navy
could end up losing training ranges or access to airspace or the
sea that it cannot afford to lose.
</P>
<P>
   ''We cannot give it away or we will never get it back,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Army chief of staff, Gen. Eric Shinseki, said he would
support a new round of base closings. On a ''cautionary footnote,''
he added that the Army needs to decide whether it needs to increase
or decrease its manpower before it can say with certainty what
should be done about consolidating bases.
</P>
<P>
   Among the service chiefs, only Air Force Chief of Staff Gen.
Michael Ryan vigorously advocated more closings.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need it badly,'' Ryan said, not just to save money but to
correct a situation in which communities near Air Force bases are
resisting the service's efforts to consolidate forces because they
fear such moves are setting the stage for an eventual base closure.
This has left the Air Force in ''gridlock,'' Ryan said.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate appearance before the House Appropriations defense
subcommittee, Cohen noted that President Clinton's defense budget
for the coming fiscal year asks for authority to make base closings
in 2003 and 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Those two rounds of base closings would save $3 billion a year,
Cohen said, from 2008 to 2015. That is the time period when huge
bills will come due for some of the weapons modernization projects
now planned, he said. The Defense Department needs the savings from
base closings to help pay those bills, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In each of the past three years Cohen pressed for more base
closings and each time Congress said no. There is little indication
that he will succeed this year, either.
</P>
<P>
   The last round of base closings was approved by Clinton and
Congress in 1995. In all, the independent commission created by
Congress recommended closing 79 domestic bases and realigning 26
others, for anticipated savings of $19.3 billion over 20 years. In
the previous three closure rounds in 1988, 1991 and 1993, the
military was ordered to close 250 bases and realign 152 others.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
