<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Theater Owner Urges Valentino Oscar  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID GERMAIN, AP Entertainment Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Rudolph Valentino died three years before the
first Academy Awards. That's not stopping theater operator Charlie
Lustman from wistfully talking up the silent-screen star for an
Oscar.
</P>
<P>
   Lustman ran a rare Valentino flick, ''The Married Virgin,'' at
his Silent Movie Theatre this week, billing it as a premiere that
potentially could qualify for Academy consideration.
</P>
<P>
   However, an Academy rule put in place after Charlie Chaplin won
an Oscar for a 20-year-old film apparently will scuttle Valentino's
shot at a statue.
</P>
<P>
   Filmed a few years before Valentino's breakout role in ''The
Four Horsemen of the Apocalypse'' in 1921, a version of ''The
Married Virgin'' apparently played in very scant release under the
title ''Frivolous Wives'' in the early 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   Lustman said he thinks that version may have been substantially
different and its release so limited that the restored print he ran
might fit Oscar guidelines for newly released movies.
</P>
<P>
   Academy rules require that a movie play commercially in a Los
Angeles County theater for seven consecutive days starting no later
than Dec. 31 of the awards year.
</P>
<P>
   Because of that Los Angeles rule, Chaplin's 1952 movie
''Limelight'' became eligible for Oscars in 1972. The movie never
played in Los Angeles in its initial limited release but was shown
there when it was reissued 20 years later.
</P>
<P>
   Chaplin and two co-writers won the 1972 Oscar for musical score.
</P>
<P>
   After Chaplin's victory, the Academy added a rule excluding
films shown commercially anywhere in the United States more than
two years before its qualifying seven-day run in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ''It doesn't matter if was in Los Angeles or Dayton, Ohio. If it
played even a day before that two-year rule, it isn't eligible,''
said Academy historian Patrick Stockstill.
</P>
<P>
   Citations in trade magazines indicate the ''Frivolous Wives''
version of the movie did play briefly in the 1920s, probably
disqualifying ''The Married Virgin'' under Oscar rules, said
Jeffrey Vance, who worked on restoring the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Vance and film preservationist David Shepard began
reconstructing the movie from film obtained from a private
collector. The project was completed by the Royal Film Archive of
Belgium in 1995, the centennial of Valentino's birth. Valentino
died in 1926 of a perforated ulcer.
</P>
<P>
   Realistically, any discussion of the silent star's Oscar
potential is probably academic. While Valentino does a nice turn as
a villain in the movie and shows signs of the heartthrob he would
become, it's doubtful Academy voters would consider the role
Oscar-worthy.
</P>
<P>
   Valentino fans will get a chance to see ''The Married Virgin.''
A video release is planned this summer, Vance said.
</P>
<P>
   Lustman thinks Valentino's performance would stack up against
contemporary nominees'. Valentino plays an Italian count who
blackmails his way into marriage with a tycoon's daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Given that Samantha Morton was nominated for supporting actress
this year for a non-speaking role in Woody Allen's ''Sweet and
Lowdown,'' Valentino's performance might be equally deserving,
Lustman said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think Valentino would be a strong contender,'' Lustman said.
''There's a lot of facial expressions in this picture that are
really moving. Why shouldn't he be considered?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-02-00 1543 </TRAILER>
