<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 15:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Californians could know New York outcome before primary pollsclose  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Because of the time difference, Californians
may see balloons falling, banners waving and supporters cheering
for one or another of the presidential candidates in New York
before primary polls even close in the Golden State next week.
</P>
<P>
   What has been a quadrennial general election concern in
presidential races has surfaced eight months early this time around
because of the March 7 Super Tuesday primaries. In New York,
primary polls close at 9 p.m. local time. In California, the
polling places shut their doors at 8 p.m. Pacific time.
</P>
<P>
   That two-hour time difference could have an impact on Democrats
Al Gore and Bill Bradley and Republican George W. Bush and John
McCain, according to pollsters and politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ''The whole Northeast becomes more significant,'' said pollster
Lee Miringoff, head of Marist College's Institute for Public
Opinion in Poughkeepsie, N.Y..
</P>
<P>
   ''It has a dampening effect'' on the West Coast vote, said
California Secretary of State Bill Jones, who recently abandoned
Bush in favor McCain.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to New York and California, the March 7 primary
lineup includes the New England states of Maine, Massachuetts,
Rhode Island, Connecticut and Vermont as well as Ohio, Maryland,
Georgia and Missouri. All are in the Eastern time zone except for
Missouri which is in the Central time zone.
</P>
<P>
   That two-hour difference between poll closings in New York and
California had the Gore camp trying to figure out this week whether
it would be better for their California chances to have the vice
president in New York on March 7 -- they hope with celebrating
supporters -- or on the other coast.
</P>
<P>
   California's Jones has been a leader in the unsuccessful battle
to get the television networks to stop using exit poll results to
declare winners in eastern states while West Coast polls are still
open.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, then-President Jimmy Carter conceded defeat to former
California Gov. Ronald Reagan an hour before polls closed in
Reagan's home state. Even before that, the TV networks had
proclaimed Reagan's victory.
</P>
<P>
   Among pollsters, the impact of exit poll information is a
subject of some debate.
</P>
<P>
   ''If they start coloring in the map with one color and it's
McCain's or Bush's, it has a value,'' Marist's Miringoff said.
''The talk of the evening becomes that.''
</P>
<P>
   ''In the 80's when Carter conceded, that probably hurt
Democratic chances (in California), but I don't think there's any
clear-cut cases that this makes a big difference,'' Andrew Kohut,
director of the Pew Research Center and president of the National
Council on Public Polls, said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Kohut said the media has a responsibility to report the
news.
</P>
<P>
   ''Who wins New York is an important fact and it's certainly
worthy of reporting,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Republican consultant Jay Severin said the biggest impact could
be on McCain and Bradley because they are viewed as insurgents who
appeal to non-traditional primary voters.
</P>
<P>
   ''It could have a big effect, especially among people who are
not hard-core voters ... They may stay home if they think it
doesn't matter,'' Severin said.
</P>
<P>
   Pollster Miringoff said that despite the debate over whether or
not the early results can effect voting in the West, ''I've never
seen any politician not want to win early.''
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a reason they all want to be on the six o'clock news
saying how things are going their way,'' Miringoff said. ''This
would be much more convincing.''
</P>
<P>
   ''If you have a knockout punch for say Bush, it could have an
impact in California,'' Nelson Warfield, who served as Bob Dole's
1996 presidential campaign press secretary, said. ''The calendar
has always been a big ally of George W. Bush, now maybe the clock
is too.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, according to recent polls, it could be Gore who has the
clock advantage, if there is one. Polls show him leading former New
York Knicks basketball star Bradley by a wide margin in New York.
</P>
<P>
   On the Republican side, recent polls indicate Bush and McCain
are locked in a tight race in New York. Also, in New York, there is
no popular vote for Republican candidates and ballots are cast only
for prospective convention delegates. That could slow down the
process of determining a winner in New York, and keep potential
California Republican primary voters in the dark for that extra two
hours.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-02-00 1545 </TRAILER>
