<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 15:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Eyes Anti-Money Laundering Laws  </HEADLINE>
By MARCY GORDON, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration is asking Congress
for broad new powers to fight money laundering, including the
authority to ban financial transactions between offshore financial
havens and U.S. banks and brokerage firms.
</P>
<P>
   The administration is seeking to tighten anti-money-laundering
laws in an effort to stanch the flow of billions of dollars from
drug trafficking and other criminal activities through the U.S.
financial system. Money laundering came under the public spotlight
last summer, when federal authorities said the Bank of New York,
one of the country's largest banks, had served as a conduit for
about $7 billion in Russian money, some of it believed to be from
criminal activities.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual move, Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers named
specific countries as leading sources or destinations of illicit
money in a speech Thursday outlining the new legislative proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ''Money laundering risks undermining the integrity of our
financial system,'' Summers told an audience of bankers and
securities industry executives. ''When dirty money finds its way
into American banks, the reputations of all involved suffer.''
</P>
<P>
   Money laundering around the globe is estimated to absorb nearly
$600 billion annually, or up to 5 percent of the world's gross
domestic product. Profits from drug trafficking, prostitution and
other criminal activities are moved through a series of bank or
brokerage accounts to make them appear to be proceeds of legitimate
business activity.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Summers identified Russia, Colombia and Nigeria
as among the biggest sources of illicit money, and the Caribbean
islands of Dominica and Antigua, Nauru in the South Pacific and
Liechtenstein in Europe as some of the leading money-laundering
centers.
</P>
<P>
   The tiny island of Nauru, for example, has become a popular
refuge for money flowing out of Russia, and Russian mobsters have
taken advantage of its lax financial rules, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Russia, Colombia, Antigua and Nauru are working with the United
States to tighten their financial laws, but the Russian government
''has still not enacted meaningful reforms,'' Summers said.
</P>
<P>
   In the new proposal, the Treasury Department is seeking the
power to ask U.S. financial institutions to collect data on all
kinds of transactions with an offshore bank or financial company.
</P>
<P>
   In cases where foreign governments shield banks from
investigation, Treasury wants the authority to cut them off from
the U.S. financial system without seeking congressional approval.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders of the House Banking Committee liked the
administration's proposal so much they said Thursday they would
co-sponsor it in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal would provide the federal government ''with more
flexible and effective tools than those offered under existing
law'' to fight money laundering, Committee Chairman Rep. Jim Leach,
R-Iowa, and its senior Democrat, Rep. John LaFalce of New York,
said in a joint statement.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, Leach and LaFalce proposed a stricter measure that
would have required U.S. banks to collect detailed information on
their customers from countries considered to be money-laundering
havens. The administration's proposal would leave it up to Treasury
to decide whether to impose data-collecting requirements on
particular banks.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers' proposal had been opposed by the banking
industry. Groups representing the banking and securities industries
had no immediate comment Thursday on the administration's plan.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., said the Clinton proposal is ''a
good first step but it doesn't go far enough'' because it gives
Treasury discretion to decide whether to take actions rather than
requiring they be taken.
</P>
<P>
   ''Diplomacy usually prevails over the domestic need to curb
money laundering,'' Schumer said in a telephone interview. He and
Sen. Paul Coverdell, R-Ga., have proposed their own
money-laundering legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Summers noted in his speech that Treasury officials already have
begun informing U.S. banks about foreign banks or nations that
repeatedly refuse to abide by generally accepted standards to
protect against money laundering.
</P>
<P>
   In September, Treasury unveiled its first national
money-laundering strategy, a package of proposed new laws and rules
that include requirements that storefront check cashers, brokerage
firms and casinos notify authorities of suspicious activities the
way banks are required to do.
</P>
<P>
   That package, and the new proposals outlined by Summers, will be
submitted to Congress in the coming weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-02-00 1553 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000302.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Family of bombing victim dismayed that Pinochet freed  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY GOLD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- The family of a New Jersey newlywed killed
in a bombing linked to Gen. Augusto Pinochet said Thursday they are
dismayed but not surprised that the British government has released
the former Chilean dictator.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's unfortunate, I think, from the world's point of view ...
it would be good for dictators who murder people for no reason to
have some fear of God put in them,'' Murray Karpen said from his
home in West Orange.
</P>
<P>
   Karpen's daughter, Ronni Karpen Moffitt, was killed 23 years ago
in Washington, D.C., in a car bombing that also killed her boss,
former Chilean Cabinet official Orlando Letelier, a prominent
Pinochet critic.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet was freed Thursday after 16 months in custody after
Britain ruled the 84-year-old was mentally unfit to stand trial on
charges of human rights abuses. Spain, Belgium and France sought to
extradite him for trial.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has not yet decided whether to seek
extradition, the Justice Department said Thursday. The U.S.
government in the summer asked Chile to supply information on the
bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet is expected to return to Chile, where his opponents
seek a trial. A Chilean government report says 3,197 people were
murdered or disappeared at the hands of Pinochet's secret police,
but opponents say the number is far higher.
</P>
<P>
   Karpen, 71, said he doubted the opponents will prevail: ''He'll
live out his years in peace. No one else will have any peace.''
</P>
<P>
   He and his son, Harry S. Karpen, 47, said they expected the
release.
</P>
<P>
   ''It seemed to be a road that Britain didn't want to go down,''
the younger Karpen said from his Clifton law office. He noted that
the extradition of a former head of state from another country
could pose risks for other leaders who traveled abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, he is angry that the man many believe responsible for
his older sister's death is unlikely to be held accountable.
</P>
<P>
   ''Look at what Britain has done: Using humanitarian grounds for
someone who has never shown humanity,'' he said. ''Just because a
killer has gotten old and infirm, doesn't mean he's eligible for
special privileges''
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for Moffitt's widower and Letelier's widow, Samuel J.
Buffone, said they are convinced the Washington bombing -- within a
mile of the White House -- went higher than the two secret police
leaders now serving prison terms in Chile.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's incomprehensible to us that something of the magnitude of
an assassination in the United States, given the relationship
between the U.S. and Chile, could have been carried out without
Pinochet's active involvement,'' Buffone said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet was considered an American ally during the Nixon
administration because he opposed communism.
</P>
<P>
   Buffone's clients seek a ''full and fair trial'' of Pinochet,
preferably in the United States, and have no private claims
pending, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Moffitt's widower, Michael Moffitt of Princeton, was riding with
his wife and Letelier on Sept. 21, 1976, but survived the explosion
and later remarried.
</P>
<P>
   He did not immediately return a message left with his lawyer
seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Ronni Moffitt was 25 when she died, just four months after her
marriage in the back yard of her family home, then in Passaic, her
father said. She had just been promoted to fund-raiser from
secretary at the Institute for Policy Studies in Washington, where
Letelier was based, Karpen said.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet stepped down after 17 years as Chile's leader in 1990.
He was arrested Oct. 16, 1998, while getting medical treatment in
London on a warrant issued by a Spanish investigating judge.
</P>
