<HEADLINE> Illegal Alcohol Sales Targeted  </HEADLINE>
By JIM ABRAMS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Senate committee approved legislation
Thursday to give state prosecutors more weapons to combat illegal
interstate alcohol sales. Lawmakers first made changes to meet the
concerns of small wineries and Internet sellers.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, endorsed by the Senate Judiciary Committee on a
voice vote, permits the attorney general of a state to file in
federal court for an injunction to stop illegal shipments of
alcohol into the state.
</P>
<P>
   Direct interstate shipments of alcohol ''are increasing
exponentially,'' said Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, chairman of the
committee and sponsor of the legislation. States need to protect
their citizens from consumer fraud, receive their rightful tax
revenues and ''ensure that minors are not provided with unfettered
access to alcohol.''
</P>
<P>
   Without the ability to go to federal court, state prosecutors
say they have trouble pursuing charges against out-of-state
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Internet companies have voiced concern that the bill could
restrict electronic commerce, and small wineries have viewed it as
a threat to the fast-growing Internet portion of their business.
Direct sales by phone or the Internet now account for an estimated
$500 million of the $17 billion industry, and are crucial to small
wineries with limited marketing capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch sought to ease some of the concerns by amending his bill
to make clear that injunctions would be allowed only if a person is
or has been engaged in an act that violates state law. He also
added language stating that the bill does not conflict with the
moratorium on Internet taxation and that Internet providers would
not be subject to injunctive action as a result of users selling
alcohol illegally.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., who had previously opposed the
bill, also got Hatch to incorporate language making clear that no
court can enforce a state law that is unconstitutionally
protectionist and discriminates against out-of-state sellers.
</P>
<P>
   The Wine Institute, based in San Francisco, said the new version
was an improvement over a bill the Senate passed last year. The
institute, in a statement, said it was important to note that the
bill ''would not in any way impact the direct shipment of wine in
the 20 states that allow interstate shipments or the 30 states that
allow intrastate shipments from wineries or retailers directly to
consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   The prohibition-lifting 21st Amendment to the Constitution gives
the states the right to regulate the sale and transport of alcohol
across state borders and many states strictly control shipments,
requiring producers to go through wholesalers. The Internet allows
wineries to bypass wholesalers and retailers.
</P>
<P>
   The House last year passed a similar bill sponsored by Rep. Joe
Scarborough, R-Fla. The Senate attached its alternative as an
amendment to a juvenile crime bill that failed to emerge from a
House-Senate conference committee.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bill number is S. 577.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
