<HEADLINE> Census 2000 Timeline  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   The Census Bureau undertakes a count of the
population every 10
years, with the data used to redraw political boundaries and
reallocate federal aid. The following is a list of key dates for
the 2000 census:
<TEXT>
<P>
   --March 3: First census forms delivered to rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   --March 3-April 15: Census Bureau allows people to respond to
questionnaires via their Web site, www.census.gov.
</P>
<P>
   --March 13: Census-takers go out to survey selective rural areas
that may be hard to reach, such as Indian reservations; forms
mailed out to rest of the country
</P>
<P>
   --March 26: Census Bureau begins releasing localized mail
response rates over its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   --March 27-29: Census-takers go out to survey homeless
population.
</P>
<P>
   --March 31: Census-takers go out to survey others in the
transient population -- people who have no permanent address but are
not homeless, such as traveling carnival workers, those who live in
campgrounds, or those who live on boats; also, extra census forms
made available at questionnaire centers and other local venues such
as supermarkets, post offices.
</P>
<P>
   --April 1: Date that census data is supposed to be based on -- the
census is actually a survey of who lives where on April 1, 2000;
also, census survey of people living in ''group quarters,'' such as
prisons, dormitories and military bases begins.
</P>
<P>
   --April 27-July 7: Census-takers go out to survey those
households that did not mail back their census forms.
</P>
<P>
   --June 19-Aug. 19: Accuracy and Coverage Evaluation survey
begins, a randomly sampled survey of 300,000 households that will
be use to statistically correct results (for sampling purposes).
</P>
<P>
   --Dec. 31: Delivery of actual head count (non-sampled) data to
President Clinton; data must be used for purposes of reapportioning
of Congressional seats.
</P>
<P>
   --April 1, 2001: Sampled data is released.
</P>
<P>
   Source: U.S. Census Bureau.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
