<HEADLINE> Red-Hot Parisian Fall Fashion  </HEADLINE>
By SUZY PATTERSON, AP Fashion Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- A red-hot Parisian, beret and all, is how Sonia
Rykiel sees winter.
</P>
<P>
   Her ready-to-wear collection, shown Thursday, featured models
strutting in layered, wide jersey trouser suits with tunics and
shawls, in tomato red as well as shocking pink, bright acid green
and turquoise.
</P>
<P>
   Striking multicolored striped sweaters with a panel on one
sleeve and bright plaid wide-trousered outfits with nubby wool
jackets were upbeat and fetching. The heavy-knit long beige coat
with a cloche, plus bright pink metallic stiletto shoes looked like
a modern comeback of the ''Roaring Twenties.''
</P>
<P>
   A few tributes to Miss Rykiel's favorite black came out in
sequined dresses, nearly-nude net numbers with bikini pants and a
bias-cut black and white satin gown.
</P>
<P>
   A fake fur spotted pantsuit was out of tune with the usual
Rykiel style, but fit the current mood here.
</P>
<P>
   In this season of glitz and logo-mania, Rykiel didn't hesitate
to put her name in spangles on some pretty, bright sweaters.
</P>
<P>
   The Kenzo collection by Gilles Rosier had something for
everyone, from biker pants to folklore galore.
</P>
<P>
   The colorful result was a success for Rosier. He took over for
Kenzo, who decided to retire for other pursuits. Rosier had worked
several years for Kenzo and understands the philosophy: fun,
picturesque clothes that will sell.
</P>
<P>
   The silhouette this time had its Japanese touch, with wide
obi-style hip belts in leather or satin.
</P>
<P>
   In dresses, tights and long or abbreviated trousers,
animal-stripe and spotted prints abound, and even look good with
wispy chiffon outfits.
</P>
<P>
   An idea: pants split at the hip to show what's underneath,
whether a patch pattern of sequins on the thigh or a crochet
bodysuit.
</P>
<P>
   Blazing colors from turquoise to pink came out in full long
skirts, but sequined moments were rare, though seen in sparkly
motifs on a bosom under a tuxedo jacket.
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Paul Gaultier's collection should be a commercial success,
despite his showtime gimmick. He stuffed over 1,000 people into an
ancient firetrap dance hall, the Salle Wagram, to watch models
smoking as they paraded to a voice telling them ''Smoking is bad
for you.''
</P>
<P>
   The show had an Andes air to it, with some big shawl wraps,
beautiful short or high boots, and little brimmed trilby hats in
all colors.
</P>
<P>
   The girls in slinky skirts, bright tights and high heels also
looked like ''Paris Apaches,'' that avant-garde set from the
Thirties, sometimes adorned with furs on their jacket or coat
collars.
</P>
<P>
   Great lean leather pants in every autumnal shade, from chocolate
to khaki green or sienna, came out topped with neat boleros, long
sweaters in luminous knits or trench coat styles. Dressy tops in
light fabrics went well with the super hard-edge pants.
</P>
<P>
   The touch of class? In furs and smooth leathers in colors like
burnt orange or sienna.
</P>
<P>
   Some complained that Gaultier had abandoned his wild and crazy
ways with Madonna-style corsets and other skin-baring fare.
</P>
<P>
   This was not a costume party, but a fine collection from the
fashion upstart-turned couturier.
</P>
<P>
   The team designing for Guy Laroche turned in an honorable
effort. A leather teal-blue suit with a low waist and skirt below
the knee looked salable if not exactly world-shaking.
</P>
<P>
   Interesting here were the true leathers and leather-like
synthetics with patterns like circular mosaics, in colors from
black to butterscotch and caramel. Mohair and taffeta in a fitted
light beige coat looked attractive with swirly patterns.
</P>
<P>
   The clothes in the intriguing, supple fabrics were easy to wear,
and well cut. But a big name like Guy Laroche might look for a guru
to give more pizzaz to the collections.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
