<HEADLINE> Russian mob allegedly joined Italian crime families in stockscheme  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Russian mobsters teamed up with four Italian
organized crime families in New York to infiltrate Wall Street in a
stock scam that earned them up to $60 million in profits,
authorities said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The unusual combination of forces led to millions in profits
before the FBI stumbled upon documents in a storage locker that
revealed the large-scale stock fraud and money laundering plot,
investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   A four-year probe culminated in an indictment unveiled Thursday
in Brooklyn. In all, 19 people were charged, including six alleged
mobsters or associates of crime families, all of them accused of
participating in the scheme between 1993 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those charged had been captured earlier in a similar
prosecution in U.S. District Court in Manhattan. That case involved
stock manipulation by small brokerage houses protected by the mob.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney Loretta E. Lynch said the case ''illustrates the
continuing relationship of organized crime in the stock market.''
</P>
<P>
   The mob, she said, ''sought to extend its reach into the lives
of ordinary citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Though she estimated the scheme made at least $40 million in
illegal profits, Lewis Schiliro, the FBI's assistant director in
charge of the New York office, said actual profits could easily
exceed $60 million.
</P>
<P>
   He said the case proved once again that Italian organized crime
families, closed off from traditional avenues of income through
aggressive prosecutions, had looked elsewhere for new
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ''A recurrent theme in our investigations has been that the mob
goes where the money is,'' he said. ''We intend to be there when
they get there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Russian gangsters used their expertise in money laundering
and offshore bank accounts while the New York mob families lent
their skills at muscling their way to money through threats and
intimidation, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities refused to divulge exactly how the organized crime
families protected the scheme or if anyone was injured.
</P>
<P>
   Schiliro said help from the mob was welcomed by two now-defunct
brokerage firms in downtown Manhattan -- White Rock Partners &AMP; Co.
and State Street Capital Markets Corp.
</P>
<P>
   According to the indictment, top executives at the two companies
joined other brokerage firms and brokers to create fraudulent
securities schemes and then launder tens of millions of dollars of
illicit profits.
</P>
<P>
   The firms allegedly acquired control of tiny companies by
quietly buying enough stock in them, then artificially boosted
their value by paying unscrupulous brokers to persuade unwitting
investors that they should buy stock in the same companies.
</P>
<P>
   After the stock value rose six or seven points, the firms cashed
in by selling their secretly held shares, causing the value of the
stocks to plummet, the indictment alleged.
</P>
<P>
   The profits were laundered by transferring money several times
through off-shore bank accounts until it had the appearance of
having been legitimately earned.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch said one company whose securities were manipulated by the
mob was essentially dormant until it became part of the scheme.
Three companies, she said, were listed on the NASDAQ exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Among those indicted in the case were a captain in the Bonanno
crime family, a soldier in the Genovese family, an associate in the
Colombo family and an associate and a soldier in the Gambino
family.
</P>
<P>
   Schiliro said the companies who solicited help from the mob
learned over time that organized crime had become part of their
business.
</P>
<P>
   ''Once they're in, they're in for good,'' Schiliro said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-02-00 1650 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000302.0056 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Welcomes Vaccine Donations  </HEADLINE>
By ANNE GEARAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton said Thursday he will work
to get more money for vaccines and drug research at home and abroad
to ''eradicate the leading infectious killers of our time.''
</P>
<P>
   The president welcomed leaders of pharmaceutical and
biotechnology companies, public health foundations and
international organizations to the White House, where he announced
the private sector donation of millions of doses of vaccines. The
drugs will go to fight malaria, hepatitis B, polio and other
diseases that kill more than 1 million people each year, mostly in
the Third World.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today we're building a partnership to eradicate the leading
infectious killers of our time,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Four major drug companies also pledged to speed research and
development on vaccines for HIV/AIDS and malaria. Clinton has
proposed a $1 billion tax credit over 10 years to encourage the
development of such vaccines.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a very important beginning,'' Clinton said. ''It will
save lives and make it clear we're serious. But all of us agree
there is more to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton appealed for support in Congress for his tax credit
plan, as well as funding increases for the National Institutes of
Health. He also wants $50 million toward a global vaccine bank, and
more loans from the World Bank devoted to improving health in
developing countries.
</P>
<P>
   And Clinton said he will ask America's economic allies to make
similar commitments when he attends the G-8 summit in Okinawa,
Japan in July.
</P>
<P>
   Infectious diseases kill more than 8 million children worldwide
and orphan millions more annually. In Africa, 10 times as many
people died from AIDS last year as were killed in wars.
</P>
<P>
   Although sub-Saharan Africa contains a tenth of the world's
population, the region is home to 70 percent of those infected with
the AIDS virus worldwide, and 13 million children there have lost
one or both parents to the disease.
</P>
<P>
   A persistent problem in fighting AIDS and other diseases in the
Third World is the lack of a profit motive for drug companies,
since the very poor cannot afford vaccines that are extremely
costly to develop and manufacture.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's meeting in the Cabinet Room was intended to draw
attention to that problem, and to solutions that do not necessarily
involve government.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Gates Sr., father of the Microsoft billionaire, attended
Thursday's meeting in the Cabinet Room because the Gates family
foundation has donated $750 million to help buy vaccines for poor
people.
</P>
<P>
   ''For a 21st century problem we have what I think is, for the
first time, a 21st century solution,'' Treasury Secretary Lawrence
Summers said after attending the meeting, ''the coming together of
governments, of the private sector, of the philanthropic foundation
community to address this common problem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
