<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Considers Education IRAs  </HEADLINE>
By JANELLE CARTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Ignoring a veto threat, the Senate moved
closer Thursday to passing a bill that would expand tax-free
savings accounts for elementary and secondary school education,
including private school tuition.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, most of whom oppose the measure, tried to add several
amendments, including an unsuccessful attempt to spend $1.7 billion
to train and recruit more teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Senators were expected to tackle several other Democratic
amendments throughout the evening and hoped to vote late Thursday.
Pending proposals include measures to force the Senate to commit to
a timetable to act on gun control -- a response to this week's
shooting of a 6-year-old girl at a Michigan school and a provision
to increase federal money for Pell grants which go to needy college
students.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the underlying battle over the bill stemmed from concerns
by Democrats that the education accounts will hurt public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ''The bill is going to shortchange our public schools,'' said
Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J. ''When we say we're going to provide
our citizens with an option, the option is more or less to abandon
the public school systems, particularly in our urban centers which
are struggling.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans countered that the time for education accounts' had
come, and accused Democrats of trying to dilute the measure with
amendments.
</P>
<P>
   ''The main effect (of the amendments) is to cancel the education
savings account,'' said Sen. Paul Coverdell, R-Ga., and chief
sponsor of the bill along with Democratic Sen. Robert Torricelli of
New Jersey. ''You're saying to 14 million American families, 'Sorry
Charlie, we're not going to let you create an education savings
account.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which would also make savings in prepaid tuition plans
tax free and expand tax breaks for employer-provided educational
assistance, is a mainstay of the Republican agenda for improving
K-12 education.
</P>
<P>
   The measure has not yet come up in the House, where its
prospects are uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   Education savings accounts have existed since 1997 to help
families save for college, but Republicans want parents to have the
option of using the funds to pay for secondary and elementary
education also.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is opposed by teachers unions, and President Clinton
vetoed a similar bill in 1998. He said the benefits mainly go to
richer families and that the plan would drain money away from the
public school system. Last year, education savings accounts were
part of the Republican's $792 billion tax cut plan that the
president vetoed.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we are really fundamentally asking ourselves how we can
improve education, it's not through a tax credit. ... It's
investing in teachers in our public schools,'' said Sen. Jack Reed,
D-R.I.
</P>
<P>
   The Coverdell-Torricelli bill would increase the contribution
level from the current $500 to $2,000 and allow the tax-free
earnings to be used for expenses, including transportation and
tutors, associated with any school -- public, private or parochial --
from kindergarten through the 12th grade.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans added provisions to raise the income levels a
married couple could earn and still participate in the program from
a $160,000 maximum to $220,000. Lawmakers also passed a proposal by
Delaware Sen. William Roth, the Finance Committee chairman, to
allow the budget surplus to pay for the proposal, estimated to cost
less than $10 billion over 10 years. Roth's amendment also makes
the program permanent; it was originally scheduled to last until
2003.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
