<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Campaign finance advocate says PACs aren't the problem  </HEADLINE>
By CAREN BENJAMIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Connecticut congressman who once advocated
banning PAC money in federal campaigns took donations from
political action committees in the last election cycle.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Christopher Shays, a seven-term Republican, said he changed
his mind because ''I found out PACs weren't where the problem
was.''
</P>
<P>
   He stressed that he never promised to forswear PAC money
indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, Shays said, is ''soft money'' -- unregulated
donations to political parties -- and so-called ''issue
advertisements'' paid for by special interest groups but clearly
aimed at supporting or damaging a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not accepting any support from soft money and I have never
been part of an issue advertising campaign. If people did them for
me I would ask them to stop,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His opponent in the GOP primary, high school teacher Jim
Campbell, said Shays has ''broken his word and violated our
trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Shays, who represents Connecticut's 4th District, was a lead
sponsor of a 1996 sweeping campaign finance reform measure.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would have banned PAC contributions, created voluntary
spending limits, limited lobbyist contributions and banned soft
money.
</P>
<P>
   A later version of the bill would have limited PAC contributions
to the same amount as individual contributions, $1,000 per
election. Now PACS can give up to $5,000 per election.
</P>
<P>
   The current version focuses mainly on soft money and issue
advertisements. That measure passed the U.S. House of
Representatives in September 1999.
</P>
<P>
   When the legislation banning PACS was pending, Shays said he
felt he clearly needed to make a point in his own campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But in the course of participating in debates on campaign
finance he said he became convinced that PACS were nothing more
onerous than a group of like-minded people coming together around
an issue.
</P>
<P>
   From July to the end of December 1999 Shays accepted $2,279 from
four political action committees, including a group that supports
pro-choice Republicans and an insurance company.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the $178,794.05 he raised that period was from
individual donors.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Martin Meehan, D-Mass., Shays' campaign finance reform
co-sponsor, said he promised never to take PAC money. He says he
agrees with Shays that PACs are not the real problem, in part
because ''it's easy to trace where the PAC money comes from.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
