<HEADLINE> In New York, Gore reads to children, Bradley plays serves hot dogs  </HEADLINE>
By SANDRA SOBIERAJ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Beneath a colorful alphabet board, Vice
President Al Gore drew a lesson on loyalty Thursday from ''A Friend
for Little Bear,'' before excoriating the Republicans' education
agenda as ''an afterthought.'' Bill Bradley played native New
Yorker at a hot dog joint.
</P>
<P>
   Both Democratic presidential candidates raced full tilt toward
New York's March 7 primary -- perhaps Bradley's last best hope for a
comeback -- but on little sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Arriving from Los Angeles just as dawn broke, Gore had two hours
at his hotel before he spent another two hours with The New York
Times editorial board, courting the newspaper's endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   He netted an informal nod from former Vice President Walter F.
Mondale, who told WCCO radio in Minneapolis that he recently
promised Gore his support ''and I guess I'm announcing it now.''
The 1984 Democratic nominee plans to appear with Gore in Minnesota
next week.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley met Thursday with editors at the Spanish-language daily
newspaper El Diario and sat for interviews with three New York TV
stations. On his own red-eye flight from California, where he and
Gore debated Wednesday, a jovial Bradley imitated the body
contortions of reporters curled up in sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ''I slept for two hours,'' he said. ''That's all you need for a
hot dog stand.''
</P>
<P>
   At Gray's Papaya, a popular juice and hot dog eatery in lower
Manhattan, Bradley donned a red employee jersey, plucked hot dogs
from the grill, nestled them in buns and laid them on the counter.
He downed his own sauerkraut-and-mustard topped hot dog in three
bites before flying on to Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, he planned to mine Maine and Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   At Public School 163 on the city's Upper West side, Gore read to
5- and 6-year-olds about a stuffed bear who forsook his playmate,
Wooden Horse, for a pile of material goods.
</P>
<P>
   ''What's more important, things or a friend?'' Gore asked the
two dozen children at the foot of his rocking chair. ''You
shouldn't leave a friend alone or take a friend for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   To parents in another classroom, Gore blasted Republican
presidential rivals John McCain and George W. Bush for supporting
private-school vouchers that Gore said would drain funds from
public schools. ''They seem to think that just because schools in
New York begin with P.S., that education is just an afterthought.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore never mentioned Bradley, and campaign aides likewise looked
beyond the primary fight.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope we secure the nomination in a timely manner so we can
move on to other priorities,'' said campaign manager Donna Brazile,
with an eye on Gore's strained budget.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's daughter, Karenna, was hosting a Washington fund-raiser
Thursday night while her dad, who took the night off after stopping
at a Maryland school, was playing babysitter to Karenna's infant
son, Wyatt, according to aides. At Francis Scott Key Elementary
School in District Heights, Md., Gore read the Dr. Seuss classic,
''Green Eggs and Ham'' to about 50 children. He also used the visit
to press his plans for universal preschool, and expansion of Head
Start and early childhood education programs.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was returning to New York on Saturday for another pair of
fund-raisers. A top campaign official estimated that, by Bradley
remaining in the race at least through next Tuesday, Gore would
spend $5 million he could otherwise save for the general election.
</P>
<P>
   In a Friday trip to Jacksonville, Fla., Gore was picking up an
endorsement from Sen. Bob Graham, who can help carry Florida for
Gore in the fall campaign, campaign officials believe.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who has lost every nominating contest yet to Gore, is
banking on a resurgence in the Northeast, where the former New
Jersey senator and New York Knicks basketball star is better known
than anywhere else in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Entering the final days before the March 7 ''Super Tuesday''
primaries potentially decide the nominee, Bradley hoped to pump up
his appeal with a five-minute paid prime-time appearance Thursday
night on CBS. In the ad, Bradley says he wants to be president ''to
use the power of that office to do good.''
</P>
<P>
   But in New York, where Bradley was running even or ahead just
eight weeks ago, polls released this week showed Gore leading
2-to-1. New York's Tuesday ballot offers 243 delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's state headquarters remained determinedly upbeat, with
staffers answering the phones, ''It can happen in New York!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
