<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Louima jury focuses on Turetzky testimony  </HEADLINE>
By TOM HAYS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A jury deliberating in the trial of three police
officers charged with conspiring to conceal one's role in the
bathroom torture of Abner Louima focused Thursday on the testimony
of an officer who helped break the case.
</P>
<P>
   Before ending their second day of deliberations in Brooklyn
without a verdict, jurors sent U.S. District Court Judge Eugene
Nickerson a note asking to be read a transcript of the
cross-examination of Eric Turetzky. The jury was to resume
deliberating on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   At trial, Turetzky -- now a detective in the police Internal
Affairs Bureau -- testified that as a Brooklyn patrolman he helped
arrest Louima during a street disturbance in the summer of 1997; an
assault charge against Louima was subsequently dropped. He
identified Charles Schwarz as the officer who led the handcuffed
prisoner toward a bathroom in the 70th Precinct station.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors used that identification last year to help convict
Schwarz, 34, of violating Louima's civil rights by leading him into
the bathroom and holding him down while another officer, Justin
Volpe, sodomized the Haitian immigrant with a broken broom handle
in a fit of rage. Schwarz faces a possible life sentence.
</P>
<P>
   The government claims that while Turetzky broke a supposed
''blue wall of silence'' -- the unspoken code among officers not to
''rat'' on each other -- Schwarz and two other officers were engaged
in a cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors have relied on records showing Schwarz and
codefendants Thomas Bruder, 33, and Thomas Wiese, 36, made a flurry
of phone calls to each other as investigators zeroed in. The
pattern and timing of the calls proved the officers were trying to
''get their stories straight'' to protect Schwarz by saying he was
never in the bathroom, they said.
</P>
<P>
   The defense tried to convince the jury there was no conspiracy
by arguing the alleged cover story was indeed true. Volpe, who
pleaded guilty to the attack and is serving 30 years in prison,
emerged as a key defense witness. He testified that Wiese -- not
Schwarz -- was there with him, but did not participate in the actual
assault.
</P>
<P>
   Schwarz himself testified last week that during Volpe's attack,
he was outside the building, inspecting his patrol car.
</P>
<P>
   On cross-examination, Turetzky was confronted with a 1997
statement in which he said he had seen Schwarz enter the bathroom
with Louima -- a detail later dropped from his account. He blamed
the discrepancy on a ''poor choice of words on my part.''
</P>
<P>
   The jurors, eight women and four men, began deciding the
defendants' fate Wednesday after Nickerson told them that by law
they ''need not determine the extent of any role the defendant
Schwarz may have played in the sexual assault.''
</P>
<P>
   The defendants face terms of up to five years if convicted on
obstruction of justice charges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-02-00 1742 </TRAILER>
