<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Minn. Sen. To Block FEC Nominee  </HEADLINE>
By JIM ABRAMS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Democratic senator said Thursday he would
block action on a Republican-backed nominee to the Federal Election
Commission who has been an outspoken opponent of laws that restrict
campaign spending.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Paul Wellstone, D-Minn., said he was putting a ''hold'' on
the nomination of Bradley Smith, a Senate parliamentary tactic that
can effectively prevent a confirmation vote.
</P>
<P>
   ''We know where Bradley Smith stands and that is far out of step
with the desire of Americans to clean up our political system,''
Wellstone said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, professor at an Ohio law school, has been at the center
of controversy since last year when Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott, R-Miss., temporarily delayed confirmation of Richard
Holbrooke as U.S. ambassador to the United Nations to protest
President Clinton's delay in naming Smith to the FEC post.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was the choice of Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., the
Senate's most tenacious foe of legislation to restrict campaign
funding.
</P>
<P>
   The FEC, which enforces federal campaign finance law, is made up
of six members, three chosen by Senate Republican leaders and three
by Democratic leaders. The president traditionally goes along with
the decisions of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton last month announced he would nominate Smith, but
stressed that he did so with great reluctance. ''There's a reason
they wanted Bradley Smith on the FEC,'' Clinton said of his
Republican sponsors. ''You know, he hates campaign finance
reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith has argued that current campaign finance law has failed to
rid the system of corrupting influences while unconstitutionally
infringing on free speech, and says he would prefer a system with
no limits on how much candidates can raise and spend.
</P>
<P>
   But he has also said that if confirmed by the Senate he would
work within the law.
</P>
<P>
   Both Democratic candidates for president, Vice President Al Gore
and former Sen. Bill Bradley, have condemned Smith's nomination and
Senate Democratic leader Tom Daschle of South Dakota said this week
that ''Mr. Smith's complete disdain for federal election law
renders him unqualified for the role of an FEC commissioner.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
