<HEADLINE> Dow Ends Up 26.99; Nasdaq Slips  </HEADLINE>
By EILEEN GLANTON, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed in a volatile session Thursday
as investors took profits from a recent rise in technology stocks
but continued buying blue chips that were battered last week.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the market was nervous in advance of Friday's
scheduled release of the government's employment report.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average was up 26.99 at 10,164.92.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Nasdaq composite index
ended down 29.57 at 4,754.51 after rising as much as 44 points in
early trading. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index rose 2.57 to
1,381.76.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow's gains were led by AT&AMP;T, which rose 6 5/16 to 54 3/16
after Goldman Sachs reminded investors that the company remains on
its list of recommended stocks. AT&AMP;T was also helped along by the
latest flurry of takeover talk in the telecommunications sector.
</P>
<P>
   Telecom shares headed higher amid rumors that Germany's Deutsche
Telekom wants to acquire a U.S. company -- perhaps Global Crossing.
Deutsche Telekom's U.S.-traded shares rose 8 13/16 to 97 1/16, and
Global Crossing gained 3 7/16 to 54].
</P>
<P>
   SBC Communications and BellSouth, which are believed to be
discussing a combination of their wireless businesses, also rose.
SBC, a Dow stock, was up 3 to 45 and BellSouth rose 1~ to 44~.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow was also boosted by blue-chips that tumbled last week
amid worries over interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Investors believe ''enough was enough'' after last week's
pummeling of Dow and other industrial stocks, said Gregory Nie,
technical analyst at First Union Securities in Chicago. ''This
week, volume has picked up and breadth is better, and the market is
trying to rally. That is encouraging.''
</P>
<P>
   IBM rose 3 to 103\ and General Electric gained 3~ to 135\.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq slumped despite an explosive initial public offering
from Palm Inc., the spinoff of 3Com Corp. Shares of Palm soared
from its offering price of 38 per share to 57 1/16. Parent company
3Com, which has risen sharply in recent sessions, tumbled 22 5/16
to 81 13/16.
</P>
<P>
   Several other prominent technology companies slipped, suggesting
that investors were selling shares of companies that have performed
well this year to raise cash to buy lesser-known names in the
technology and Internet fields.
</P>
<P>
   Radiant Systems, for example, soared 28[ to 83] after the
company said it will work with Microsoft to develop electronic
commerce systems.
</P>
<P>
   Trading was fairly volatile, indicating that the interest rate
worries responsible for the Dow's plunge last week clearly are
still in the market.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday morning, most leading retail companies reported robust
sales, suggesting Americans are spending freely despite four rate
increases by the Federal Reserve since last June.
</P>
<P>
   Higher rates make it more expensive to borrow money. The Fed has
been raising rates in an effort to slow the economy to a pace that
will allow continued growth without inflation.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, investors will receive crucial information on the
economy's strength from the Labor Department's employment report
for the month of February. The report will include information on
wages and benefits, which should indicate whether companies are
spending heavily to attract and keep employees while the U.S.
jobless rate lingers at extremely low levels.
</P>
<P>
   ''That report is responsible for a lot of the volatility we're
seeing,'' said Sam Stovall, senior investment strategist at
Standard &AMP; Poor's Corp. Many on Wall Street have begun to believe
that a report of lower-than-expected unemployment could prompt the
Fed to raise rates even before its next meeting in March.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's some fear of a pre-emptive rate increase,'' Stovall
said.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 4-to-3 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange. NYSE composite volume totaled 1.45 billion
shares, compared with 1.54 billion in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 4.31 to 584.04.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.1 percent.
European indexes were sharply higher after the European Central
Bank left interest rates unchanged. Germany's DAX index rose 2.8
percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 gained 1.1 percent, and France's
CAC-40 rose 3.5 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
