<HEADLINE> Liggett: Reynolds discount cigarette pricing violates antitrustlaws  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY GOLD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- Liggett Group Inc. on Thursday charged that
fellow cigarette maker R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co. broke federal
antitrust laws by paying retailers to raise the prices on discount
cigarettes sold by RJR competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Liggett claimed that in return for RJR's payments under its
''Every Day Low Pricing'' program, retailers agreed that no
discount cigarettes would be sold for less than an RJR discount
brand.
</P>
<P>
   In a lawsuit filed in U.S. District Court here, Liggett said
''this is accomplished, not by lowering the price of the RJR
product, but by raising the prices of other competing products.''
</P>
<P>
   RJR's contracts are an unreasonable restraint of trade that
prohibit retailers from lowering the prices of competing products
''even if RJR's competitors offer substantial discounts to the
retailer for the purpose of lowering the retail price,'' the
lawsuit said.
</P>
<P>
   The program has led to nationwide cigarette price increases and
reduced Liggett sales, the lawsuit said.
</P>
<P>
   RJR spokesman John Singleton said the company had not yet
reviewed the lawsuit but maintained, ''R.J. Reynolds Tobacco
Company's pricing policies are well within the limits of all laws
and regulations that cover pricing.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither company could immediately say when the ''Every Day Low
Pricing'' program started.
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie Herzog, a tobacco industry analyst at CS First Boston,
questioned whether such a pricing program is really in place.
</P>
<P>
   She said the typical retailer programs by RJR and other tobacco
companies are similar to those in other industries, in which the
companies reduce prices for prime shelf placement and signage. In
return, the retailer can sell for less and increase volume.
</P>
<P>
   RJR has said it has raised prices 82 cents a pack over the
previous two years to offset costs from the 1997 $206 billion
settlement with 46 states.
</P>
<P>
   Liggett claimed the program has ''no legitimate business
justifications,'' allows RJR to fix the price of its competitor's
products, and prevents competitors from entering the market.
</P>
<P>
   ''Liggett is unable to maintain or increase sales not because of
weakened consumer demand but because of the chokehold that RJR has
placed at the retail level of the relevant market, preventing
Liggett from competing on price and substantially reducing the
volume of Liggett's sales and profits,'' the lawsuit said.
</P>
<P>
   Liggett declined to give figures.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit seeks an injunction barring RJR from using the
pricing program, and unspecified compensatory and punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   RJR, the nation's No. 2 cigarette maker, is based in
Winston-Salem, N.C., but is incorporated in New Jersey, where it
has a sales office in Edison.
</P>
<P>
   Liggett, the fifth-largest tobacco company, is part of
Miami-based Brooke Group Ltd. It sells Pyramid brand discount
cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   RJR markets the top-selling discount brand, Doral, shipping 26.6
billion Doral cigarettes in 1999, down 13.5 percent from 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Doral's retail market share slipped from 6.24 percent in the
first quarter last year to 6.20 percent in the fourth quarter,
according to Marlin retail-market share figures, the industry's
leading retail-market source.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Doral remained RJR's top-selling cigarette in 1999 and held
the second-best market share among all domestically sold
cigarettes, behind Philip Morris' premium brand Marlboro.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-02-00 1833 </TRAILER>
