<HEADLINE> Bush backers Pataki and Giuliani battle over McCain criticism  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Five days before New York's presidential
primary, George W. Bush's best-known supporters in the state -- Gov.
George Pataki and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani -- are battling each other.
</P>
<P>
   The infighting comes at a bad time for Bush, with polls showing
him running neck-and-neck with John McCain in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every top New York Republican has endorsed the Texas
governor's candidacy. But Giuliani, who is running for the Senate
against Hillary Rodham Clinton, has refused to join Pataki in
criticizing McCain. In fact, he has repeatedly said nice things
about the Arizona senator.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Pataki and his political allies launched a
coordinated attack against McCain, citing his Senate voting record
as being ''as anti-New York ... as anybody's in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani refused to allow his name to be used on a mailing
criticizing McCain. And he balked at attending a news conference
Thursday with other mayors from across New York, also meant to
attack McCain's voting record.
</P>
<P>
   Zenia Mucha, Pataki's spokeswoman and one of his top political
advisers, said Thursday of Giuliani, ''If you're going to be
defending the state in the Senate, you have an obligation to point
out another senator's votes against your interests and those of the
constituency you want to represent.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani political aide Bruce Teitelbaum, after consulting with
the mayor, said there would be no harsh words from his boss against
McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mayor Giuliani believes that it should be possible in American
politics to strongly support someone, as Mayor Giuliani does George
W. Bush, and not bash their opponents with negative attacks,''
Teitelbaum said. ''For Mayor Giuliani, it's a matter of principle
and it's rooted in his respect and friendship with both
candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been bad blood between Pataki and Giuliani since the
mayor crossed party lines in 1994 to endorse then-Gov. Mario Cuomo
over Pataki. Among other things, Giuliani questioned Pataki's
ethics. Pataki won the election.
</P>
<P>
   It was Bush's intervention last year that led to Pataki's
backing for Giuliani's Senate campaign. At the time, Bush was
looking for a peaceful New York scene in which he could coast to
victory in any GOP primary. That notion disappeared with McCain's
resounding victory in the New Hampshire primary and rising poll
numbers elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Giuliani and Pataki said both still planned to
accompany Bush on a campaign trip across the state on Friday and
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is hoping to make inroads in New York, especially with
the 46 percent of Republican voters in the state who are Roman
Catholic and may be upset by Bush's visit last month to Bob Jones
University in South Carolina as part of his appeal to the religious
right. Some school leaders are known for anti-Catholic views.
</P>
<P>
   In something of a surprise, the Bush camp scrapped plans
Thursday for a visit to Fairfield University in Connecticut on
Friday and one to Canisius College in Buffalo, N.Y., on Saturday.
Both are Catholic schools.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Karen Hughes said Bush had two stops scheduled
in each of several areas and any events that have been moved or
canceled were only because ''we're trying to hit more media
markets.''
</P>
<P>
   She said that Bush visited a Catholic Charities site early in
the week in Cleveland and on Wednesday went to St. Louis
University.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
