<HEADLINE> Detained Librarian Addresses House  </HEADLINE>
By CLAUDE R. MARX, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A librarian detained by the Chinese government
for nearly six months told a House subcommittee Thursday that his
experience shows the need for more outside pressure on China to
improve human rights.
</P>
<P>
   Song Yongyi, a Chinese-born librarian at Dickinson College in
Carlisle, Pa., who became an American citizen last month, said he
learned firsthand that the Chinese legal system still has ''so many
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Song was doing research for a book on China's Cultural
Revolution when he and his wife were arrested Aug. 7. Chinese
authorities eventually freed his wife but accused Song of spying
and kept him in custody.
</P>
<P>
   ''I argued with those policemen in every interrogation on every
charge and I won every time. However, these secret agents told me
they would still sentence me,'' he told the House subcommittee on
international operations and human rights.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese authorities freed Song on Jan. 28. Chinese Ambassador Li
Zhao Xing said the move came after Song showed ''repentance'' for
his crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Song says he never admitted any wrongdoing. He told lawmakers
that after the Chinese released him an official told him they did
so because they feared U.S. economic sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Other witnesses told the subcommittee that Song's experience was
not unusual.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights activist and former political prisoner Harry Wu
described China as a ''government that does not know the meaning of
individual dignity.'' He said the government still uses forced
labor and penalizes people who have more babies than the government
allows.
</P>
<P>
   Wu said because of these abuses, Congress should not grant China
permanent most favored nation trade status this year. The Clinton
administration backs the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Subcommittee Chairman Chris Smith, R-N.J., said ''the already
despicable behavior of the Chinese communist regime has gotten
worse in every category of human rights concern.'' Because of those
conditions, granting most favored nation status ''ought to be
unthinkable at this point in time.''
</P>
<P>
   AFL-CIO President John Sweeney agreed and said Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright is ''dreaming'' when she argues that the
United States can only maintain leverage if it gives China the
trade status.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
