<HEADLINE> NRC says corrosion from inside is likely cause of leak  </HEADLINE>
By JIM FITZGERALD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUCHANAN, N.Y. (AP) -- The Nuclear Regulatory Commission said
Thursday that last month's accident at the Indian Point 2 power
plant was probably caused by superheated, highly pressurized water
corroding a nickel-alloy tube from the inside.
</P>
<P>
   NRC spokesman Neil Sheehan emphasized that an official finding
is weeks away and ''there are other pieces of that puzzle that we
still have to look at.'' But based on a videotape from a
remote-controlled camera sent into the tube, ''it's probable that
this was stress corrosion cracking,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 15, radioactive water heated in the reactor leaked from
one of the generator's 32,000 tubes into the clean water that
surrounds them. As a result, there was a small discharge of
radioactive steam into the atmosphere. There were no injuries and
the increase in radioactivity was too small to be measured,
officials said. Still, it was the worst accident in the plant's
26-year history.
</P>
<P>
   If corrosion does turn out to be the cause, it could draw into
question the industry's inspection practices. Con Edison, which
operates the plant 35 miles north of Times Square, said its last
inspection in 1997 showed no suggestion of a crack in the tube that
leaked. The plant has had less than two years of operating time
since then, and the NRC granted Con Ed's request for a year's
postponement of an inspection scheduled for June 1999.
</P>
<P>
   NRC investigators suggested at a Wednesday night meeting with
Con Ed that if the crack could appear, deepen and break open
between inspections, the inspection schedule might have to be
tightened.
</P>
<P>
   ''If necessary, we will re-evaluate our own standards,'' said
Brian Sheron, the NRC's associate director for project licensing.
</P>
<P>
   ''The lesson clearly is that it doesn't make sense to relax the
inspections. They should be more stringent,'' said Edwin Lyman,
scientific director of the Nuclear Control Institute in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Con Ed Vice President Stephen Quinn said a decision on more
frequent inspections should be made ''on sound, technical
knowledge'' not passion and should await the completion of the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn said the water in the tube starts out in a highly purified
state and is much less corrosive than ordinary tap water. But
because it is heated to 500 degrees and pressurized to 2,200 pounds
per square inch, it can stress the tube that carries it.
</P>
<P>
   David Lochbaum, nuclear safety engineer for the Union of
Concerned Scientists in Washington, said that ''even though the
water is very close to pure, the fact that you have such high
temperatures and pressures makes any amount of impurities gain a
foothold and propagate.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheehan also noted that the leak occurred in a U-shaped portion
of the tube, which imparts additional stress, and that water flows
through it at rates up to 70,000 gallons per minute. The tube's
inside diameter is seven-eighths of an inch and the thickness of
its walls is one-twentieth of an inch.
</P>
<P>
   ''You wanted to have it as thin as possible to get a good
transfer of heat and the belief was that this material would hold
up very well over time to those sort of pressures and temperatures,
but they have been more susceptible to corrosion than initially was
believed,'' Sheehan said.
</P>
<P>
   James Riccio, senior analyst at Public Citizen in Washington,
said the alloy in the tubes, called inconel 600, has been shown to
be subject to stress problems even when exposed to pure water.
</P>
<P>
   ''The problem isn't the water,'' he said. ''The problem is Con
Ed has water-soluble steam generator pipes.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the utility should be forced to install replacement
generators they have owned since the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Lochbaum said that if the current inspection finds other tubes
in the generators have been corroded and stressed, they should be
replaced or there could be another tube rupture.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-02-00 1841 </TRAILER>
