<HEADLINE> Lawmakers hear from family members of inmates shipped to Virginia  </HEADLINE>
By ADAM GORLICK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Family members of Connecticut inmates
moved to a Virginia prison slammed the relocation plan Thursday,
saying it has unfairly added to their punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Doris Arroyo of Hartford said her son has become depressed and
suicidal in the three months since he was moved to Wallens Ridge
State Prison.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's very stressing, and he's getting worse,'' Arroyo said.
</P>
<P>
   She said her son, Armando Arroyo, has a mental illness and isn't
getting any help for it at the super-maximum security prison in Big
Stone Gap, Va. She said her son -- who is serving a 10-year sentence
for convictions on drug charges -- is rarely allowed to make phone
calls or receive mail.
</P>
<P>
   ''We used to visit him every week,'' said Betsy Burgos, Armando
Arroyo's girlfriend. ''But now it's too far. I don't know when
we'll ever see him.''
</P>
<P>
   Joyce Gumbus said guards at Wallens Ridge have denied her son
access to religious materials.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's bad enough they moved him away from me,'' the Stamford
woman said. ''Now they won't let him have a bible.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of the state's Public Safety, Judiciary and
Appropriations committees heard testimony Thursday on a bill
calling for a study of the prison transfers.
</P>
<P>
   Since October, 480 prisoners have been moved to Wallens Ridge.
Gov. John G. Rowland has said transferring prisoners saves money
because the per-inmate cost is cheaper at in the Virginia prison
than in Connecticut. The transfers also allow the state to manage
the size of Connecticut's crowded inmate population while weeding
out troublesome prisoners, Rowland said.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut's contract with Virginia's Department of Correction
allows 500 inmates to be housed at Wallens Ridge for $11 million a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Some key lawmakers say the transfers may be unnecessary, and
want to study whether some offenders in Connecticut can be put in
treatment or rehabilitation programs rather than taking up needed
prison cells.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are a lot more mentally ill people filling jails in
Connecticut than we need there,'' said Rep. Michael Lawlor, D-East
Haven. ''There are people in our prisons who would be better served
in other environments.''
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Fabian agrees.
</P>
<P>
   During the three years he was locked up in a Connecticut prison
for stealing a leaf blower out of a garage, he said he never got
treatment for his drug addiction, attention deficit disorder and
short-term memory problems.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is very hard to get help, and I never got what I needed in
prison,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But some cautioned against having too much sympathy for jailed
drug addicts.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nobody is incarcerated because they're a drug addict,'' said
Rep. Robert Farr, R-West Hartford. ''They're incarcerated because
of what they did when they were drug addicts.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislation being considered by lawmakers would also
increase the state's oversight of Connecticut inmates at Wallens
Ridge.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawmakers have accused guards at the Virginia prison of
racial intolerance. Their complaints that the warden of Wallens
Ridge displayed prints of Civil War battle scenes featuring the
Confederate flag prompted the pictures to be removed.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing comes as the FBI investigates allegations of abuse
made by New Mexico inmates who were shipped to Wallens Ridge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
