<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State guide details banking fees  </HEADLINE>
By KATHLEEN CANNON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Customers tired of paying high banking fees
now have a resource to steer them toward cheaper banks.
</P>
<P>
   The state Department of Banking and Insurance on Thursday
released the first Consumer Guide to Bank Fees, a comprehensive
listing of fees charged on 649 accounts by 158 banking
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   The guide, which is also available on the Internet, lists fees
imposed on consumers who use ATMs, bounce checks, purchase cashier
checks, or conduct other banking business.
</P>
<P>
   The guide shows that most, 97 percent, of New Jersey banks allow
customers free use of ATM machines at their own bank. A smaller
ratio, 85 percent, impose no monthly service charge for ATM cards.
</P>
<P>
   But most banks charge non-customers a token fee of $1 or $1.50
per transaction. A handful of banks charge $2, including First
Morris Bank and Trust, St. Edmond's Federal Savings Bank, Sun
National Bank and Valley National Bank, according to the guide.
</P>
<P>
   Fees for other services, such as overdrafts, general service and
checking accounts, vary from bank to bank, according to the guide.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman said consumers can use the information to
shop around for the best rates.
</P>
<P>
   ''One of the best things we can do is give consumers the tools
to make intelligent decisions and this Web site and consumer guide
are two tools that will enable them to make informed decisions,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   If enough consumers act on the information, they may be able to
put pressure on banks that charge high fees to lower them, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The marketplace reacts,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor said she is reluctant to place government controls
on the banking industry to reduce or eliminate ATM or other banking
fees.
</P>
<P>
   But a Whitman critic said the data call into question Whitman's
hands-off policy.
</P>
<P>
   ''The governor's survey and guide is a non-solution that only
allows consumers to pick their own ATM fee poison,'' Sen. Wayne
Bryant, D-Camden, said in a prepared statement.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no leadership from an administration that is
effectively saying, ''Here's an ATM survey - it shows how banks are
ripping you off,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The guide is the result of a December survey conducted by
department officials of every bank in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman said the survey will be repeated and the guide updated
twice a year to provide the most recent information to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   It can be obtained by calling 1-800-446-SHOP or by accessing the
state's Web site: www.state.nj.us.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-02-00 1903 </TRAILER>
