<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shoe expert says print on slain suspect's shirt similar toofficer's boot  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LITCHFIELD, Conn. (AP) -- A pattern found on the back of the
bloody shirt worn by a slain suspect is consistent with the print
of a boot worn by the New Milford officer charged in his murder, a
renowned forensic expert testified on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Former FBI agent William Bodziak took the stand for nearly two
hours as the prosecution wrapped up its case against Scott Smith,
the first police officer in the state ever charged with murder for
an on-duty incident.
</P>
<P>
   Bodziak, a footwear impressions specialist, has testified at the
O.J. Simpson trial and the Oklahoma City bombing trial.
</P>
<P>
   He testified that the imprint was made by a Timberland boot like
those Smith was wearing the day of the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, 28, has said he shot Franklyn Reid to death during an
arrest on Dec. 29, 1998 when Reid made a sudden move from knees, as
if reaching for a weapon. But prosecutors contend that Bodziak's
testimony backs up an account from a passing motorist who said she
saw Smith standing over Reid as the suspect lay face down. Reid was
shot in the back at point-blank range.
</P>
<P>
   State's Attorney John Connelly has called several expert
witnesses this week in an attempt to show that Reid was on his
stomach and not on his knees as Smith claimed.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Virginia Maxwell, a state forensic scientist testified
Wednesday that grass and soil stains on Reid's clothing were
consistent with the prosecution theory. She said she did not find
heavier stains at the knees.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Wednesday, a firearms expert testified that the gunshot
could not have been an accident.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement to his attorney, Smith said he fired to kill. And
state firearms expert Edward McPhillips said the Hoechler&AMP; Koch
handgun has a safety mechanism to prevent accidental discharge.
</P>
<P>
   ''You must squeeze the cocking device on the grip to cock it and
dislodge the safety mechanism,'' he explained, holding the small
black handgun. ''The trigger cannot be pulled without squeezing the
grip.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense is expected to begin its case on Friday.
</P>
