<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cost of N.M. Ranch Said Too High  </HEADLINE>
By MATT KELLEY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The $101 million Congress set aside to buy a
New Mexico ranch is up to 2{ times more than the property is worth,
auditors said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the purchase criticized the General Accounting
Office report even before its formal release, which could come
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''This ranch has been called the Yellowstone of the Southwest.
It's a magnificent resource,'' said Rep. Tom Udall, D-N.M., whose
district includes the ranch. ''We need to get it into public hands
so all the people of New Mexico can use it.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress must approve the purchase and a new management plan for
the 95,000-acre Baca Ranch by April 30. Supporters fear the report
could derail the purchase agreement with the Texas family that owns
the land.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO review, called for under the law setting aside about
$1,060 an acre for the ranch, said comparably sized ranches in the
Southwest had sold for $400 to $670 an acre. That range would put
the price tag for the Baca Ranch between $38 million and $63.7
million.
</P>
<P>
   Asked by the GAO to respond, the U.S. Forest Service said last
week the review came to the wrong conclusions. The GAO auditors did
not even visit the ranch, which is ''widely considered one of the
most spectacular natural and scenic areas of the nation still in
private ownership,'' the Forest Service said.
</P>
<P>
   ''When we pay $101 million, we are paying the fair market value
of a property that is special and which cannot be duplicated
elsewhere in the market place,'' the Forest Service said.
</P>
<P>
   The Baca Ranch deal was the largest single component of $651
million Congress set aside to buy and preserve open space this
year. Udall and other supporters say the GAO ignored the land's
special value for recreation and conservation.
</P>
<P>
   The ranch in the Jemez Mountains north of Santa Fe is home to
thousands of elk and other wildlife and includes an extinct
volcano, the Valles Caldera. The ranch also features hot springs,
sulfur pools and six valleys.
</P>
<P>
   The ranch is owned by the Dunigan family of Abilene, Texas. It
is almost completely surrounded by the Santa Fe National Forest and
the Bandelier National Monument.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
