<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Parents of SIDS victims push for standards on infant autopsies  </HEADLINE>
By THOMAS MARTELLO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Their voices quivered, and tears welled up.
The hearing room grew quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Then four young parents looked into the eyes of strangers and
talked about the most personal and horrifying moment of their
lives: when they discovered their seemingly healthy babies had died
in their sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ''My daughter Heather was 20 months old, and we had put her down
for a two-hour nap,'' said Robin Alda, 33 of Howell. ''She woke up
that morning healthy, smiling and happy ...''
</P>
<P>
   ''Our son passed away during the night, and so did a piece of
us,'' said Jim Adams, 32, of Flemington. ''I'll never forget my
wife's bloodcurdling scream ...''
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers on the Assembly Health Committee listened intently
Thursday, then passed a bill that would set standards for the
autopsies of babies who die without explanation. The bill, A-1984,
now advances to the full Assembly. It has already passed the state
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   For parents whose children died of Sudden Infant Death Syndrome
or other causes, the loss is made worse when authorities cannot
shed much light on why they died.
</P>
<P>
   ''Losing a child is the most tragic event you can ever
experience,'' said Alda. ''Not knowing what happened is a
double-whammy.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters say setting a uniform standard for autopsies could
provide some answers for parents, and add more reliable scientific
data that can be added to the national research on SIDS. Sponsors
said autopsies now focus primarily on the potential of crime, to
rule out child abuse. They said medical questions should be probed
and recorded. The bill would set a strict autopsy protocol for
babies who die of SIDS and require all county medical examiners to
follow it.
</P>
<P>
   ''We all come from different circumstances,'' said Laura
Crandall, 31, of Montclair. ''But all our children were healthy
until the moment they died. And we all want peace of mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Crandall said more than two years after her 15-month-old
daughter, Maria, died, she still has no answers. An initial finding
of a heart attack was later ruled out. She said by the time she was
supplied with samples of her daughter's tissue for another opinion,
they could not be studied.
</P>
<P>
   Such unanswered questions have an impact beyond parents'
emotions. Because they don't know what happened to their babies,
their other children are often subjected to medical testing to rule
out a wide range of diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Alda said her 8-month-old daughter has gone through ''countless
tests. We don't know what it was. We don't know if it was genetic,
or what.''
</P>
<P>
   The parents showed photographs of their smiling babies, some
taken hours before they died. They also brought their other
children: some recently born; others who remember the younger
sibling who left them too soon.
</P>
<P>
   ''Just before I came up to talk to you, my 6-year-old daughter,
Jen, whispered to me,'' Marriane Gonzalez, 37, of Berkeley Heights,
told the committee. ''She said, 'Mommy, other babies went to sleep
and didn't wake up, just like Matty. I'd like to know what
happened.'''
</P>
<P>
   When she heard her name, young Jennifer jumped out of her chair
and nodded her head. Gonzalez, who couldn't see Jennifer, continued
to talk.
</P>
<P>
   ''I told her, 'We'd all like to know,''' Gonzalez said. ''We'd
all like to know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-02-00 1923 </TRAILER>
