<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Work Begins on HMO Legislation  </HEADLINE>
By KAREN GULLO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Lawmakers from the House and Senate started
work Thursday on compromise legislation that would afford Americans
some rights when dealing with HMOs and health plans.
</P>
<P>
   The House and Senate passed bills last fall that contain many of
the same patient protections. But the two bills differ on two
touchy issues -- whether Americans should be allowed to sue HMOs and
whether a federal patient protection law should apply to everyone
or only to those whose plans are not already regulated by states,
many of which have already passed their own patients' rights laws.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats argue that patients need protections from HMOs and
managed care plans, which control costs by eliminating unneeded
care. Republicans say lawsuits will drive up health care costs and
force employers to drop coverage.
</P>
<P>
   But with patient rights a popular issue among voters, GOP
lawmakers in the House joined Democrats last fall to pass a
bipartisan patients' rights bill that allows lawsuits and applies
to all people with private insurance. The Senate bill, crafted by
Republicans, doesn't allow lawsuits and applies to fewer people.
</P>
<P>
   A bipartisan committee appointed to draft a compromise was
meeting for the first time today. Here, in question and answer
format, are key aspects of the debate:
</P>
<P>
   Q: What proposals are on the table?
</P>
<P>
   A: The House and Senate both have bills giving patients a
variety of rights, including:
</P>
<P>
   -- Ability to appeal HMO care decisions to an outside panel.
</P>
<P>
   -- A guarantee of access to reasonable emergency room care.
</P>
<P>
   -- Ability to see pediatricians and obstetricians without
permission from primary care doctors.
</P>
<P>
   -- Getting timely access to specialists.
</P>
<P>
   -- A requirement that plans not prohibit doctors from telling
patients about all their medical options.
</P>
<P>
   -- Coverage of care associated with clinical trials.
</P>
<P>
   Both bills would also allow anyone to buy medical savings
accounts, which let people set aside money, tax-free, to pay for
routine care, and would let self-employed people deduct from their
taxes what they spend to purchase their own insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are the main differences between the two proposals?
</P>
<P>
   A: They differ on two issues -- who is covered and whether health
plans can be sued.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill would apply to every American with private health
insurance -- an estimated 161 million people. Most provisions of the
Senate bill would apply to people insured through employer-based
plans that are exempt from state regulation -- about 55 million
people. One exception is a requirement that plans let patients
appeal to an outside review panel if care is denied -- that would
apply to everyone with private health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill would allow patients to sue HMOs, the Senate bill
would not.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who is working on the compromise and how long will it take?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are 20 Republican and 13 Democratic members of Congress
on the committee working on a compromise. They have set a tight
deadline of March 31.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
