<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers approve broader version of Megan's Law notifications  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Assembly members are looking to overhaul
Megan's Law by listing all sex offenders in public registries
available for free in the mail and on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   And Gov. Christie Whitman appears to be on board with expanding
sex offender notifications in some way, though she is undecided on
the specifics.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly Law and Public Safety Committee in a 7-0 vote on
Thursday approved legislation to make sex offenders' names,
addresses, employment and photos available to all for the asking
with no restriction on how they could use them.
</P>
<P>
   The current Megan's Law provides for community notification of
neighbors or of local schools and day care centers on convicted sex
offenders who have been released from prison and who pose some risk
of repeating their crimes.
</P>
<P>
   But judges in a series of rulings in state and federal courts
have placed strict limits on how these notifications are to be
conducted and who is to receive them. In New Jersey, a person who
gets a sex offender notification and shares the details with others
is violating a court order and faces sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for the new bill, A-432, acknowledged that their
proposal could shatter the delicate legal construction supporting
the current law.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the published registry would be available to all,
including community groups, businesses, real estate offices and the
news media.
</P>
<P>
   Further, while the current law has different degrees of
notification for offenders according to whether they pose a high
risk or a moderate risk, the registries would list them all.
</P>
<P>
   ''More people than the immediate neighbors are in need of this
information,'' said the sponsor, said Assemblyman Joel Weingarten,
R-Essex.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman James Holzapfel, R-Ocean, the committee chairman,
said, ''These are people who have forfeited their right to be
anonymous.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitman's spokesman, Peter McDonough, said the governor ''is
foursquare behind the idea of expanding Megan's Law to provide New
Jerseyans greater protection from dangerous sex offenders,'' but
she is awaiting advice from Attorney General John Farmer on what
form it should take.
</P>
<P>
   Former U.S. Rep. Dick Zimmer pressed for the original Megan's
Law and authored a federal version. He testified Thursday in
support of the proposed change.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer said he believes a tougher law will survive federal court
challenges, perhaps not at the lower levels but certainly before
the U.S. Supreme Court. Zimmer said the nation's highest court has
approved similar sex-offender notifications in other states.
</P>
<P>
   A number of advocates for Megan's Law said the existing law has
proven to be too limited. Among these is Maureen Kanka, who
recently told The Associated Press that she would push for the
Internet listing. It was her daughter, Megan, who became the
namesake of these laws here and across the United States after her
1994 murder at the hands of a convicted sex offender who lived
across the street.
</P>
<P>
   A sponsor of the 1995 law, Sen. Peter Inverso, R-Mercer, said he
is willing to help Kanka with an Internet registry law in the upper
house. Kanka said she has met many frustrated parents in her visits
to schools and PTAs who question why they are not informed about
the whereabouts of sex offenders.
</P>
<P>
   Weingarten, a candidate for Congress in the 7th district, said
while the 1995 ruling by the state Supreme Court required tight
limits on the information, the personnel of the high court has
changed and a different view on the issue might be expected.
</P>
<P>
   The current chief justice, Deborah Poritz, was New Jersey
attorney general in 1995 when she presented the state's case on
behalf of Megan's Law before the high court. The landmark Megan's
Law ruling bears her name, Doe v. Poritz.
</P>
<P>
   While the 1995 ruling was 6-1, all seven justices favored strict
limits on notifications to balance them with the privacy rights of
the ex-convicts.
</P>
<P>
   Of these seven justices, four have left the court including the
author, former Chief Justice Robert Wilentz, who died in 1996. A
fifth justice, Daniel O'Hern, is set to retire within two months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-02-00 2011 </TRAILER>
