<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Rides Gun Control Momentum  </HEADLINE>
By TERENCE HUNT, AP White House Correspondent
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Seeking momentum on gun control from the
Michigan school shooting, President Clinton summoned leaders of
Congress to the White House next week, hoping to break an impasse
on mandatory gun safety locks and gun show background checks.
</P>
<P>
   ''Maybe this tragic death will help,'' the president said
Thursday, referring to Tuesday's fatal shooting of a 6-year-old
girl by a classmate using a stolen .32-caliber semiautomatic gun in
Mount Morris Township, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   On Capitol Hill, there was talk of compromise between
Republicans and Democrats after months of inaction.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'll take whatever we can agree on -- gun shows, clips, safety
locks,'' said Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D. ''We're
currently doing nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill, chairman of the House Judiciary
Committee, said, ''We have a reasonable gun bill. If the Democrats
want a bill, we can do it. If they want the issue, we'll have the
issue.'' He said he was open to compromise. ''I think the country
wants legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats failed on a 49-49 tie vote Thursday night to get the
Senate to adopt a resolution calling for final congressional action
on new gun control measures by April 20. Had he been there, Vice
President Al Gore could have broken the tie, as he did last year on
a key vote before the Senate passed gun restrictions to Clinton's
liking. The legislation has been stalled since then.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton appeared to leave the door open on whether he might
accept a bill that lacked a requirement for background checks at
gun shows. Asked if he would veto such a bill, he said, ''Well, I
don't know. I think they'd have a very hard time explaining why
they did it.''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said later that Clinton was not trying to
signal flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   Always an emotional issue, the gun control debate has even more
prominence because of the Michigan school shooting and the
approaching one-year anniversary of the tragedy at Columbine High
School in Littleton, Colo., last April 20. Tensions also have been
heightened by the struggle between Democrats and Republicans for
control of the White House and Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton accused the Republican-run House and Senate of ignoring
gun control legislation for eight months. ''They have done nothing
and meanwhile ... every single day there are 13 children who die
from guns in this country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In reply, House Speaker Dennis Hastert said Democrats walked
away from a bill last year that included child safety locks and
other restrictions but did not go as far as Clinton wanted in
background checks at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope the House Democrat leadership drops its obstructionist
tactics and agrees to work with us to pass common-sense gun
legislation,'' said Hastert, R-Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Complaining of the congressional impasse, Clinton said, ''I
don't think most Americans have any idea what a stranglehold the
NRA (National Rifle Association) has had on this Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Disputing the NRA's contention that the Justice Department is
lax about prosecuting criminals, the president said, ''We have a
higher percentage of people in jail than all the other advanced
countries, and they have a lower gun death rate.''
</P>
<P>
   Wayne LaPierre, executive vice president of the NRA, said
Clinton could have had an NRA-backed bill last year that would have
required safety locks, instant gun-show checks and other
provisions. But he said Clinton insisted on restrictions that even
some key Democrats revolted against.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's being marketed as a safety-lock bill and gun-show-check
bill when actually what it is a phone-book volume of federal
regulation that only hits the law abiding, not the criminal,''
LaPierre said in an interview. ''That's our problem with it.''
</P>
<P>
   He said gun manufacturers already provide safety locks. ''All
you're doing is codifying existing practices,'' LaPierre said.
''It's all just politics. It has nothing, in my opinion, to do with
making America safer, and that's sad.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke about guns during interviews with Katie Couric of
NBC's ''Today'' show, with CBS anchor Dan Rather and during a
Cabinet Room meeting.
</P>
<P>
   On CBS, Clinton noted that the estimated 200 million handguns in
circulation pose ''a practical problem'' for an effective licensing
program covering only new gun purchases.
</P>
<P>
   ''But I think if we would begin the process of making handgun
owners get a license before they can buy a gun, pass a Brady
background check, and then have a gun safety course, I think it
would make a difference,'' said Clinton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
