<HEADLINE> Japanese Stocks Slip  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar was higher against the yen early Friday,
carrying over much of its strength in New York. Japanese stocks
slipped.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar bought 107.78 yen, up 0.43 yen from late Thursday but
lower than its late New York level of 107.83 yen.
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 98.56 points,
or 0.49 percent, to 19,966.55 points in the first 30 minutes of
trading. On Thursday, the average closed down 16.56 points, or 0.08
percent.
</P>
<P>
   In currency dealings, the dollar gained some ground amid renewed
concern that Japanese finance authorities may intervene to stop the
yen's rise.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, Japan's government has expressed concern about
gains by the yen, as a higher yen makes this country's exports less
cost-competitive abroad and decreases the value of overseas
earnings when repatriated.
</P>
<P>
   In other currencies, the euro was traded at 103.84 yen, down
from 104.97 yen late Thursday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   On the stock market, prices were lower early Friday as many
players sold export-related shares because of the stronger yen.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the last few days, the yen has appreciated, which is not so
good for export-related issues,'' said Tsuyoshi Nomaguchi, a
strategist at Daiwa Securities.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 26.99 points
to 10,164.92 points at Thursday's close.
</P>
<P>
   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section was down 13.38 points, or 0.78 percent, to 1,705.10.
The TOPIX had closed down 6.76 points, or 0.39 percent, the day
before.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond was
unquoted in early trading. On Thursday, it settled at 1.7800
percent and its price stood at 100.16.
</P>
</TEXT>
