<HEADLINE> Exxon Mobil Sells Calif. Refinery  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- Exxon Mobil Corp. announced Thursday it has
reached a deal to sell a refinery and 340 service stations in
California to Valero Energy Corp. for $895 million.
</P>
<P>
   The giant oil company had agreed to sell the refinery and
stations as a condition for winning regulators' approval of last
year's merger between Exxon Corp. and Mobil Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators had asked Irving-based Exxon Mobil to sell the
refinery in Benicia, just northeast of San Francisco, to an
independent oil company in order to avoid further concentrating the
refining industry in California, which is burdened by gasoline
prices above the national average.
</P>
<P>
   Other bidders for the refinery had included Ultramar Diamond
Shamrock Corp. and Tesoro Petroleum Corp. Like Valero, both are
based in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's hard to imagine a better strategic investment for Valero
and its shareholders,'' said Bill Greehey, Valero's chairman and
CEO.
</P>
<P>
   ''The retail business is a natural growth area for Valero
because retail margins tend to be counter-cyclical to those in
refining,'' he said. ''And, our strategic plan has been to enter
the retail business through a major acquisition where we could also
acquire an experienced management team in place.''
</P>
<P>
   Greehey said the acquisition position would immediately add to
both earnings and cash flow.
</P>
<P>
   Valero has five other refineries with a combined daily capacity
of 735,000 barrels. With four plants in Texas and Louisiana, Valero
is the largest independent refiner on the Gulf Coast. The Benicia
refinery has a capacity of 130,000 barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission required Exxon Mobil to sell the
refinery and 2,431 service stations and other assets. In December,
Exxon Mobil sold 1,740 stations in Northeast and Mid-Atlantic
states to Stamford, Conn.-based Tosco Corp. for $860 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
