<BODY>
<HEADLINE> $5.5M to Woman in Unisys Bias Case  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID GOODMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- A federal jury has awarded $5.5 million to a
former Unisys Corp. employee who claimed the computer company laid
her off because she was a woman with children.
</P>
<P>
   Victoria Morton, 44, of Troy sued Unisys in 1996, two years
after she and 124 other Detroit employees lost their jobs in a
companywide restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   Morton worked as a consultant for Unisys and was an ''absolute
top-notch performer'' for her 17 years with the Blue Bell,
Pa.-based company, said her attorney, Raymond J. Sterling.
</P>
<P>
   ''She was told by the (personnel) director at their Chicago
regional office that she had been let go because she was a woman
with children,'' Sterling said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Morton and her husband, also a Unisys employee, had three
children when she lost her job. They now have four.
</P>
<P>
   Unisys ''stereotypically and illegally thought'' that Morton
would not be able to handle increased travel as Unisys moved from
being a mainframe computer supplier to a consulting company,
Sterling said.
</P>
<P>
   Unisys spokesman Brian Daly denied the company discriminated on
the basis of sex when it laid off Morton and indicated an appeal
was likely.
</P>
<P>
   ''Unisys vehemently disagrees with the jury's verdict,'' Daly
said. ''Our attorneys will consider all avenues for review of this
decision and then take appropriate vigorous action.''
</P>
<P>
   Unisys has 36,000 employees worldwide and had 1999 revenues of
$7.54 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are committed to fair employment, regardless of sex, race,
sexual orientation, religion,'' Daly said.
</P>
<P>
   The case went to trial Feb. 10 before U.S. District Judge Denise
Page Hood. The eight jurors deliberated for less than a day before
reaching the verdict Wednesday, Sterling said.
</P>
<P>
   The jury awarded Morton $294,000 for lost wages and fringe
benefits from 1994 until now, $3.1 million for future losses of
wages and benefits and $2.1 million for emotional distress and
damaged reputation, Sterling said.
</P>
<P>
   ''She's just elated that the jury say that it was the company's
fault and not hers,'' Sterling said. ''She hopes that this is a
victory for working mothers everywhere.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
