<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Whitman threatens state colleges with aid loss for fire violations  </HEADLINE>
By KATHLEEN CANNON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- State colleges and universities risk losing
millions of dollars in state aid if they do not make
''substantial'' progress in correcting fire code violations, Gov.
Christie Whitman said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman wrote letters to the college presidents a month after
the Jan. 19 fire at Seton Hall University that claimed three lives
and critically injured six others.
</P>
<P>
   In the Feb. 18 letter, which wasn't publicly released until
Thursday, she warned the college officials of the potential monthly
penalties if they do not correct their fire code violations within
30 days. They range from $3.6 million for Montclair State
University, to $1.5 million for Ramapo College.
</P>
<P>
   ''That is a concern we obviously have,'' she said. ''The state
is going to be monitoring and will be withholding funds if they
don't come into compliance.''
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Community Affairs, which inspects state
institutions for fire code compliance, has found more than 1,000
violations at publicly funded colleges and universities. None of
them are considered major enough to trigger immediate closure,
according to Bill Cane, director of the department's Division of
Fire Safety.
</P>
<P>
   The violations were found during inspections of classroom and
dormitory buildings conducted at various times over the past year,
Cane said.
</P>
<P>
   He said 389 violations were found at Ramapo, 368 at Montclair,
189 at William Paterson University, 124 at Kean University, 43 at
The College of New Jersey and 14 at The Richard Stockton College of
New Jersey. There were at least four found at Rowan University, but
Cane said he did not know the total.
</P>
<P>
   The number of violations for the remaining state colleges and
universities was not available. County colleges were not included
because they don't have dormitories.
</P>
<P>
   In comparison, Seton Hall, a private school, was cited for 825
violations, none of which were classified as posing imminent
danger, Cane said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the violations are common throughout the college system,
according to Department of Community Affairs spokesman E.J.
Miranda. They include overuse of extension wires, improper use of
cooking devices in dorm rooms and inoperative smoke detectors, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to deny aid payments may involve some judgment
calls, said Cane and Whitman's spokeswoman, Jayne O'Connor. For
example, the state may withhold partial payment for partial
compliance, or may release full funding if officials believe the
college is making ''substantial progress'' toward making their
facility safe.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's directive applies only to the state institutions
because, unlike private colleges and universities, the state cannot
fine the state schools for fire code violations, O'Connor
explained.
</P>
<P>
   ''We needed some sort of hammer to make sure all the violations
are addressed,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Shelly, a spokesman for the New Jersey Association of State
College and Universities, said he would have ''no comment on the
negative sanctions.''
</P>
<P>
   ''In the wake of the Seton Hall tragedy, our colleges are making
every effort to fulfill the spirit of the law and adhere to the
regulations to the extent possible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Miranda said the colleges had a mixed record of correcting
violations prior to the governor's letter. In the two weeks since
it was sent, they have improved their performance, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-02-00 2111 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
