<DOCNO> APW20000302.0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Approves Education IRAs  </HEADLINE>
By JANELLE CARTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Ignoring a veto threat, the Senate passed a
bill Thursday that would expand tax-free savings accounts to
include elementary and secondary school education and allow parents
to use the money for private school tuition.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats assailed the measure, which passed 61-37, as an
assault on the nation's public school system and the beginning step
towards school vouchers. The vote was six shy of the two-thirds
that would be needed to override a veto. Administration officials
said last week they would recommend that President Clinton veto it,
as he has twice in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ''Clearly what this bill is, is a shined up version of vouchers
that is going to steal money from public tax dollars to go to
private schools,'' said Sen. Patty Murray, D-Wash.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would increase the contribution level from the
current $500 to $2,000 and allow the tax-free earnings to be used
for expenses, including transportation and tutors, associated with
any school -- public, private or parochial -- from kindergarten
through the 12th grade.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Chuck Robb, D-Va., said Congress continues to ''play this
game that diverts resources that could be used in the public school
system.''
</P>
<P>
   ''If we get to the point where we are fully meeting our
obligations with respect to public education, I think it would be
great to help education in all areas but not until we have fully
met our responsibilities,'' Robb said.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans hailed the measure as the first step in giving the
nation's education system a much-needed boost. A few Democratic
supporters contended the measure was worth a try.
</P>
<P>
   ''No senator can come to this floor with any proposal solving
every problem,'' said Sen. Robert Torricelli of New Jersey, the
Democratic co-author of the bill. The education savings accounts
are ''the opening shot in a revolution in American education.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Paul Coverdell, R-Ga., sponsor of the bill with Torricelli,
said the bill was ''historic.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It represents new ideas in education reform for the new
millennium,'' Coverdell said. ''I only hope that President Clinton
will join the Senate in its rejection of the status quo.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats unsuccessfully attempted to attach several amendments
dealing with teacher quality, school construction and social
promotion. One that did pass, 91-7, by Sen. Richard Durbin, D-Ill.,
would establish a $7 million grant program to educate students and
parents about the dangers of gun violence, including safe gun
storage. The measure was prompted by this week's shooting of a
6-year-old girl at a Michigan school.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which would also make savings in prepaid tuition plans
tax-free and expand tax breaks for employer-provided educational
assistance, is a mainstay of the Republican agenda for improving
K-12 education.
</P>
<P>
   The measure has not yet come up in the House, where its
prospects are uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   Education savings accounts have existed since 1997 to help
families save for college, but Republicans want parents to have the
option of using the money to pay for secondary and elementary
education also.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is opposed by teachers' unions, and Clinton vetoed a
similar bill in 1998. He said the benefits mainly go to richer
families and that the plan would drain money away from the public
school system. Last year, education savings accounts were part of
the Republican's $792 billion tax cut plan that the president
vetoed.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans added provisions to raise the income levels a
married couple could earn and still participate in the program from
a $160,000 maximum to $220,000. Lawmakers also passed a proposal by
Delaware Sen. William Roth, the Finance Committee chairman, to
allow the budget surplus to pay for the proposal, estimated to cost
less than $10 billion over 10 years. Roth's amendment also makes
the program permanent; it was originally scheduled to last until
2003.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-02-00 2124 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000302.0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White couple go to court to get back the black baby born to them  </HEADLINE>
By SAMUEL MAULL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A white couple has asked a state appeals court
to let them regain custody of a black baby boy that was born to
them because of an embryo mixup in a Manhattan fertility clinic.
</P>
<P>
   Richard and Donna Fasano of Staten Island want the infant back
because they say the boy's genetic parents have broken an agreement
that guaranteed that the birth mother, Mrs. Fasano, could visit the
boy periodically.
</P>
<P>
   The boy was born to Mrs. Fasano, 37, along with a white boy on
Dec. 29, 1998. Fasano had the black baby because she was
accidentally implanted with the embryos of a black woman, as well
as with her own embryos.
</P>
<P>
   Upon learning that Mrs. Fasano had given birth to their
biological child, Deborah Perry-Rogers and husband Robert Rogers of
Teaneck, N.J., sought custody of him. The Fasanos relinquished
custody after several meetings and an agreement that provided for
frequent visits between the child and Mrs. Fasano.
</P>
<P>
   In July, State Supreme Court Justice Diane Lebedeff made the
agreement a court order. She also gave the Rogerses custody of the
baby -- born Joseph Fasano and renamed Akeil Rogers -- and ordered
that his birth certificate be changed to name the Rogerses as his
parents.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the Rogerses asked the State Supreme Court's
Appellate Division to void the agreement and stop the visitation.
They contended that Lebedeff never had the authority to order the
visits, and in any case, the two couples did not get along with
each other.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the appeals court stayed Lebedeff's order, stopping
the visitation until a full five-judge panel can hear the case.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Fasanos petitioned the same court, asking to
regain custody of the baby. They say Lebedeff erred and abused her
discretion when she gave the Rogerses custody.
</P>
<P>
   The Fasanos are relying on a procedural technicality. They say
that because the Rogerses had officially dropped all legal action
against them after they gave up physical custody of the baby in
May, Lebedeff had no case before her in which to order any changes
in the baby's status.
</P>
<P>
   The Rogerses lawyer, Bernard Clair, said, ''This appeal signals
that the Fasanos, having been thwarted in their visitation
attempts, are now seeking to throw this case into a full-blown
custody fight.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Their chances of prevailing are poor,'' Clair said of the
Fasanos. ''We doubt the Rogerses needed the Fasanos consent for
custody at all once the DNA tests revealed that they were Akeil's
genetic parents.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fasanos lawyer, Ivan Tantleff, was unavailable for comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
