<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 22:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's GDP Picking Up  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's gross domestic product shrank in the
October-December quarter but economic activity has since increased,
the head of the Economic Planning Agency said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Taichi Sakaiya said he believes GDP figures for the quarter that
ended in December will be negative, but did not give a specific
estimate. The official figures are to be released later this month.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think (GDP data) will be negative,'' he told a regular news
conference. ''The figure will be low, but I have a feeling that the
situation after that is quite strong,''
</P>
<P>
   Sakaiya cited consumption as recovering ''strongly'' in January
from its slump late last year, and noted that wage-earner spending
increased 2.3 percent in January from the prior month.
</P>
<P>
   Automobile sales were up from a year ago, net exports were a
source of strength in January, and data released earlier this week
showing there were 52 jobs available for every 100 people seeking
work in January also indicated there were bright signs in the labor
market, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's economy is struggling to emerge from its worst slump in
decades.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the government expects GDP -- the sum of all goods and
services produced in the economy -- to grow 0.6 percent for this
fiscal year, which ends March 31.
</P>
<P>
   It would be the first GDP increase in three years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
